# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: environmental-history-of-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The **Cherry Mine disaster** was a fire which occurred at the Cherry Mine, a coal mine outside Cherry, Illinois, on November 13, 1909.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The fire, which killed 259 men and boys as well as three dozen mules, is the third most deadly mine disaster in American coal mining history.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Paul Coal Company opened the Cherry Mine in order to supply coal for the trains of its controlling company, the Chicago, Milwaukee & St.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The mine consisted of three horizontal veins, each deeper than the last.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The veins were connected vertically by two shafts set some 100 yards (91 m) apart.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Both the main shaft and the secondary shaft contained wooden stairs and ladders.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The main shaft was capped by an 85-foot (26 m) steel tipple which controlled a mechanical hoisting cage.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] A large fan, located in a shunt off the secondary shaft, pushed fresh air into the mine.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The miners included a large number of immigrants, heavily Italian, many of whom could not speak English.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Boys as young as 11 years old also worked the mine.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Rather than a fixed per-hour wage, pay was based on the coal production.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] On Saturday, November 13, 1909, nearly 500 men and boys as well as three dozen mules were working in the mine.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] An electrical outage earlier that week had forced the workers to light kerosene lanterns and torches.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Some were portable, and some were set into the mine walls.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Shortly after noon, a coal car filled with hay for the mules caught fire from one of the wall lanterns.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The fire went unnoticed by workers for 45 minutes before efforts to move the fire began; however, the workers only succeeded in spreading the fire to the mine's support timbers.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The mine's large fan was reversed in an attempt to blow out the fire, but this only succeeded in igniting the fan house itself as well as the escape ladders and stairs in the secondary shaft, trapping more miners below.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The two shafts were then closed off to smother the fire, but this had the effect of both cutting off oxygen to the miners and allowing the “black damp,” a suffocating mixture of carbon dioxide and nitrogen, to build up in the mine.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Some 200 men and boys made their way to the surface, some through escape shafts, some using the hoisting cage.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Some miners who had already escaped returned to the mine to aid their coworkers.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Twelve of these, led by John Bundy, made six dangerous cage trips, rescuing many others.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The seventh trip, however, proved fatal when the cage operator misunderstood the miners' signals and brought them to the surface too late - the rescuers and those they attempted to rescue were burned to death.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] One group of miners trapped in the mine built a makeshift wall to protect themselves from the fire and poisonous gases.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Although without food, they were able to drink from a pool of water leaking from a coal seam, moving deeper into the mine to escape the black damp.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] Eight days later, the 21 survivors, known as the "eight day men", tore down the wall and made their way through the mine in search of more water, but came across a rescue party instead.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] One of those 21 survivors died two days later with complications from asthma.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] In 1910, the Illinois legislature established stronger mine safety regulations as a result of the Cherry Mine Disaster.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] In 1911, Illinois passed a separate law which later developed into the Illinois Workmen's Compensation Act.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] A monument to those who lost their lives was erected on May 15, 1971 by the Illinois Department of Transportation and the Illinois State Historical Society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] The centennial commemoration of the Cherry Mine disaster was held in Cherry from November 14 to November 15, 2009.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1909-cherry-mine-disaster] A new monument, located at the Cherry Village Hall, was dedicated to the miners who lost their lives in the disaster.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] 5 coal mine exploded near the town of Centralia, Illinois, killing 111 people.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] The Mine Safety and Health Administration of the United States Department of Labor reported the explosion was caused when an underburdened shot or blown-out shot ignited coal dust.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] The US Department of Labor lists the disaster as the second worst US mining disaster since 1940 with a total of 111 men dead.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] The mine had received numerous warnings about conditions prior to the explosion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] At that time, 142 men were in the mine; 65 were killed by burns and other injuries and 45 were killed by afterdamp.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Eight men were rescued, but one died from the effects of afterdamp.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] United Mine Workers Union President John L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Lewis testified to Congress that the secretary of the Interior, Julius Krug, had ignored warnings by inspectors that coal dust had been accumulating, which can cause explosions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] At 3:25 a.m. on March 25, 1947, electric power to the mine stopped.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Survivors testified that there was a strong blow or rush of dust for about five minutes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] One miner claimed that the dust appeared to be a black powder, while a mine employee claimed that he could smell powder smoke, though he did not enter the mine until after the explosion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] An Illinois government report claimed that the explosion was caused by buildup of coal powder, though could not find a catalyst.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Though the catalyst was likely accidental, the buildup of coal powder was due to the governmental regulators following a "weak, ineffectual, and indifferent policy toward enforcement of state mining laws".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] American folksinger Woody Guthrie wrote and recorded a song about the Centralia mine disaster entitled *The Dying Miner.* Guthrie's recording of the song is now available on the Smithsonian-Folkways recording *Struggle* (1990).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Songwriter Bucky Halker rearranged this song and recorded it for his *Welcome to Labor Land* CD (Revolting Records, 2002), a collection of Halker's renditions of labor songs from Illinois.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Halker also recorded his version of "New Made Graves of Centralia" for his CD *Don't Want Your Millions* (Revolting Records, 2000).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Halker based his version on an original recording of this song in the Country Music Hall of Fame, but the author and recording artist were unknown.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1947-centralia-mine-disaster] Along with *The Dying Miner,* Guthrie wrote two other songs regarding the 1947 disaster: "Waiting at the Gate" (from the perspective of a miner's son); and "Talking Centralia" (also known as "Talking Miner").
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The **1948 Donora smog**, also called the **Donora death fog**, was an air pollution disaster that occurred in Donora, Pennsylvania, beginning on October 27, 1948, and lasting several days.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] It was caused by hydrogen fluoride and sulfur dioxide emissions from U.S.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Steel's Donora Zinc Works and its American Steel & Wire plant during an atmospheric temperature inversion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] It killed 20 people and caused respiratory problems for 6,000 of the 14,000 people living in Donora, a mill town on the Monongahela River 24 miles (39 km) southeast of Pittsburgh.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The event is commemorated by the Donora Smog Museum.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Sixty years later, the incident was described by *The New York Times* as "one of the worst air pollution disasters in the nation's history." Even 10 years after the incident, mortality rates in Donora were significantly higher than those in other communities nearby.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Hydrogen fluoride and sulfur dioxide emissions from U.S.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Steel's Donora Zinc Works and its American Steel & Wire plant were frequent occurrences in Donora.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] What made the 1948 event more severe was a temperature inversion, a situation in which warmer air aloft traps pollution in a layer of colder air near the surface.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The pollutants in the air mixed with fog to form a thick, yellowish, acrid smog that hung over Donora for five days.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The sulfuric acid, nitrogen dioxide, fluorine, and other poisonous gases that usually dispersed into the atmosphere were caught in the inversion and accumulated until rain ended the weather pattern.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The fog started building up in Donora on Wednesday, October 27, 1948.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] By the following day it was causing coughing and other signs of respiratory distress for many residents of the community in the Monongahela River valley.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Many of the illnesses and deaths were initially attributed to asthma.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The smog continued until it rained on Sunday, October 31, by which time 20 residents of Donora had died and approximately one third to one half of the town's population of 14,000 residents had been sickened.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Another 50 residents died of respiratory causes within a month after the incident.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Two of the heroes to emerge during the four-day smog were Chief John Volk of the Donora Fire Department and his assistant Russell Davis.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Volk and Davis responded to calls from Friday night, the 29th until Sunday night, the 31st, depleting their supply of 800 cubic feet (23 m3) of oxygen, borrowing more from all nearby municipalities, including McKeesport, Monessen, and Charleroi.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The eight doctors in the town, who belonged to the Donora Medical Association, made house calls much like the firefighters during the period of intense smog, often visiting the houses of patients who were treated by the other doctors in town.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] This was a result of patients calling every doctor in town in the hope of getting treatment faster.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] It was not until mid-day Saturday, the 30th, that Mrs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Cora Vernon, executive director of the American Red Cross, had it set up so that all calls going to the doctors’ offices would be switched to the emergency center being established in the town hall.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The smog was so intense that driving was nearly abandoned; those who chose to continue driving took risks. “I drove on the left side of the street with my head out the window.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Steering by scraping the curb.” recalled Davis.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] It was not until Sunday morning, the 31st, that a meeting occurred between the operators of the plants and the town officials.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Chambon, the burgess (mayor) of Donora, requested the plants temporarily cease operations.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Westhaver, said the plants had already begun shutting down operation at around 6:00 that morning.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] With the rain alleviating the smog, the plants resumed normal operation the following morning.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Researchers analyzing the event have focused likely blame on pollutants from the zinc plant, whose emissions had killed almost all vegetation within a half-mile radius of the plant.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Davis, director of the Center for Environmental Oncology at the University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute, has pointed to autopsy results showing fluorine levels in victims in the lethal range, as much as 20 times higher than normal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Fluorine gas generated in the zinc smelting process became trapped by the stagnant air and was the primary cause of the deaths.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Further research was conducted by Mary Amdur about the effects of the smog; she was pressured to withdraw publication of these results but refused to bow.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Preliminary results of a study performed by Clarence A.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Mills of the University of Cincinnati and released in December 1948 showed that thousands more Donora residents could have been killed if the smog had lasted any longer than it had.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Steel, which never acknowledged responsibility for the incident, calling it "an act of God".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] While the steel company did not accept blame, it reached a settlement in 1951 in which it paid about $235,000, which was stretched over the 80 victims who had participated in the lawsuit, leaving them little after legal expenses were factored in.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] By 1949, a year after the disaster, the total value of the predominantly residential property in Donora had declined by nearly 10%.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The Donora Smog was one of the incidents where Americans recognized that exposure to large amounts of pollution in a short period of time can result in injuries and fatalities.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The incident was little spoken of in Donora until a historical marker was placed in the town in 1998, to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the incident.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The 60th anniversary, in 2008, was commemorated with memorials for the families of the victims and other educational programs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The Donora Smog Museum was opened on October 20, 2008, located in an old storefront at 595 McKean Avenue near Sixth Street, with the slogan "Clean Air Started Here".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Fewer than 6,000 people still live in Donora.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The Donora event led to the first large-scale epidemiological investigation of an environmental health disaster in the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] An account of the smog was published in 1950 by the noted medical writer Berton Roueché in *The New Yorker* under the title "The Fog".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Together with another article, "A Pig From Jersey" (about a mass-case of foodborne illness), this article won him the 1950 Albert Lasker Medical Journalism Award.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] "The Fog" was later included in his celebrated collection of short stories *Eleven Blue Men*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] Devra Davis' 2002 novel *When Smoke Ran Like Water* starts with the Donora Smog.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The 2009 novel *Don't Kill the Messenger* by Joel Pierson features a fictional town, Wyandotte, Pennsylvania, which became a ghost town after a smog incident, based on the Donora Smog.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] In 2023 Andy McPhee's book, *Donora Death Fog: Clean Air and the Tragedy of a Pennsylvania Mill Town*, was published by the University of Pittsburgh Press.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] An hour-long documentary, *Rumor of Blue Sky*, produced by Andrew Maietta and Janet Whitney, aired on WQED TV in April 2009.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The film features archival images and interviews with survivors of the environmental tragedy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The Donora smog incident was mentioned in Netflix's *The Crown* in 2016, when it depicted a similar incident in London in 1952.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The Weather Channel produced an episode of *When Weather Changed History* on the Donora smog incident.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The incident would be revisited in a later Weather Channel series, *Weather That Changed The World*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] The 2024 podcast "Cement City", about two journalists who live for three years in Donora, includes extensive discussion of the smog incident in episode 1.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/1948-donora-smog] In 1995, the Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission installed a historical marker noting the historic importance of the event.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had over two million copies printed and has been translated into at least fourteen languages.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] It has informed and changed the environmental movement and stimulated a widespread interest in ecology as a science.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] In the original publishing, the book begins with a set of essays under the heading "Sand County Almanac," which is divided into twelve segments, one for each month.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] These essays mostly follow the changes in the ecology on Leopold's farm near Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] (There is, in fact, no "Sand County" in Wisconsin.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The term "sand counties" refers to a section of the state marked by sandy soils).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] There are anecdotes and observations about flora and fauna reactions to the seasons as well as mentions of conservation topics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The second section of the book, "Sketches Here and There," shifts the rhetorical focus from time to place.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The essays are thematically organized around farms and wildernesses in Canada, Mexico and the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] Some of these essays are autobiographical.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] "Red Legs Kicking," for example, recounts Leopold's boyhood experience of hunting in Iowa.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The seminal essay "Thinking Like a Mountain" recalls another hunting experience later in life that was formative for Leopold's later views.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold describes the death of a she-wolf killed by his party during a time when conservationists were operating under the assumption that elimination of top predators would make game plentiful.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The essay provides a non-technical characterization of the trophic cascade where the removal of single species carries serious implications for the rest of the ecosystem.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The book ends with a section of philosophical essays grouped together under the heading "The Upshot".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold explores ironies of conservation: in order to promote wider appreciation of wild nature and engender necessary political support, one encourages recreational usage of wilderness that ultimately destroys it.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] Musings on "trophies" contrasts the way that some need a physical specimen to prove their conquest into the wilderness, though photographs may be less damaging than a trophy head to be mounted on the wall.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] He suggests that the best trophy is the experience of wilderness itself, along with its character-building aspects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold also rails against the way that policy makers need to find an economic motive for conservation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] In the concluding essay, "The Land Ethic", Leopold delves into a more appropriate rationale for conservation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] In "The Ecological Conscience" section, he wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." Leopold felt it was generally agreed that more conservation education was needed; however quantity and content were up for debate.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] He believed that land is not a commodity to be possessed; rather, humans must have mutual respect for Earth in order not to destroy it.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] He philosophizes that humans will cease to be free if they have no wild spaces in which to roam.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] In a 1990 poll of the membership by the American Nature Study Society, *A Sand County Almanac* and Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* stand alone as the two most venerated and significant environmental books of the 20th century.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The book was little noticed when published but, during the environmental awakening of the 1970s, a paperback edition turned into a surprise bestseller.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had immense popular influence and has been described as: "one of the benchmark titles of the ecological movement", "a major influence on American attitudes toward our natural environment", "recognized as a classic piece of outdoor literature, rivaling Thoreau's *Walden*".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has also had great influence on environmental thinkers: "along with *Walden* and Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring*, one of the main intellectual underpinnings of environmentalism in America".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has "attracted such overwhelming attention from environmental philosophers as a source of inspiration and ideas".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold's home, Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm, was listed on the U.S.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/a-sand-county-almanac] National Register of Historic Places in 1978, and was uplisted to National Historic Landmark status in 2009.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitrogen oxides (NOx) in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by US regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of carbonate rocks, such as limestone and marble.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China (the Minnan Golden Triangle) and Taiwan.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur dioxide pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] FGD gypsum is used in construction materials (e.g. concrete), and instead of natural gypsum it can be added to agricultural soils as a source of high-quality sulfur and calcium.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles, but measures are required to further reduce road transport emissions, more especially in Diesel vehicles.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Acid rain is now as severe a threat to the developing world, especially India and China, as it was earlier to some of the developed countries.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The purpose was to combat long-range transboundary air pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulphur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the Convention.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by emissions of particulate matter and sulphur dropping by 30-80% since 1990 in Europe and by 30-40% in North America.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of atmospheric pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Activity of the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Philippines, South Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emission allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emission allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] However, ethical arguments have been opposed to the ongoing rise of emissions trading, focusing on commodification of the atmosphere, pricing that which should not be priced, or civic responsibility.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acid-rain] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The radio art of Schafer and his colleague, has found expression in many different fields.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] While most have taken some inspiration from Schafer's writings, in recent years there have also been divergences from the initial ideas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The expanded expressions of acoustic ecology are increasing due to the sonic impacts of road and airport construction that affect the soundscapes in and around cities where the human population is more dense.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] There has also been a broadening of bioacoustics (the use of sound by animals) to consider the subjective and objective responses of animals to human noise, with ocean noise capturing the most attention.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology can also be informative of changes in the climate or other environmental changes since every day we listen to sounds in the world to identify their source such as bird, car, plane, wind, water.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] But we don't listen those sounds as a network, a mesh of relationships that form an ecology.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology finds expression in many different fields that characterize a soundscape, which are biophony, geophony, and anthrophony.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Noise is generally a by-product of increased urbanization and development.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] As our cities became more industrialized, the volume and frequency of anthrophony, man-made noise signals, increased.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Noise can alter the acoustic environment of aquatic and terrestrial habitats.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Animal biodiversity has shown to decline because of chronic noise levels in cities and along roadways.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Musician and soundscape ecologist Bernie Krause relates biophony to an orchestra, where different groups of animals in an environment make sounds at different levels to avoid overlap or competition in their communication.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Manmade noise such as jets flying over a habitat can disrupt the natural order of these sounds, even putting certain species in danger of predators.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] For example, some frogs synchronize in a way that protects individuals from attracting attention.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The noise of a jet can cause the frogs to stop or fall out of sync, temporarily breaking this effect and exposing them to other animals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] On land, animal communication is shaped by physical characteristics of an environment such as distance, range of vision, weather, and surrounding noise.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The physical layout of a habitat may impede the spread of soundwaves while air conditions can affect sound quality and speed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Animals can adapt to factors like distance by adjusting the frequency and amplitute of their calls to maximize communication effectiveness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Some species such as the urban great tits have changed the frequency of their calls to adapt.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes of particular habitats are always evolving because the activities and species that exist in those habitats changes over time.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] In terms of evolution, man-made noise is a much more recent phenomenon.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Indeed, through investigating collected recordings, ecologists can study ethology of animal acoustic communication, evolution, and development of acoustic behavior, relationships between animal sounds and their environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] However, all those ecological research goals have a precondition that those bioacoustic recordings are well investigated so that the animal species can be accurately recognized.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Scientific research has shown that it has potential to change behavior, alter physiology and even restructure animal communities.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes are composed of the anthrophony, geophony and biophony of a particular environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] They are specific to location and change over time.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology aims to study the relationship between these things, i.e. the relationship between humans, animals and nature, within these soundscapes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] These relationships are delicate and subject to disruption by natural or man-made means.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] In his book *The Tuning of the World*, Schafer used new terms like 'soundmarks' -- a specific community's distinctive sounds—and 'keynotes' -- prevalent but overlooked background sounds such as traffic—to help categorize the different elements of a soundscape.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Biophony is the study of sounds emerging from animal sources, like whale vocalizations or birdsong.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Geophony can be defined as the sounds originating from the Earth's natural processes, such as the blowing of wind or movement of waves.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Anthrophony is the soundscape defined by man-made sources, like speech or road noise.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Research on the relationship between visual and auditory experiences in urban settings finds that the positive or negative visual perceptions of a landscape can directly affect the emotional assessment of the location's soundscape.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] A pleasant view or comfortable surroundings can increase people's tolerance and even appreciation for the sounds of an environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] People's preferences for noise control have been shown to differ based on the culture and technology of the time period as well as the familiarity or practicality of certain sounds.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] For example, accepted sources of loud noise such as church bells or trucks may not bother a neighborhood as much as someone's new leaf blower, even if it is not as loud as more familiar sounds.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] This is why it is considered difficult to generalize which sounds are unwanted in a community.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Studying the soundscapes and traumatic impact of war has shown the effectiveness of noise as a psychological weapon to produce fear.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Aircraft activity has been a continuing development around the world and has some very good potential to change social-ecological systems.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] In Alaska, for example the communities are reporting that the aircraft disturb wildlife and negatively influence harvest practices and experiences.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The limited data has some restricted knowledge about the extent of aircraft activity over traditional harvest areas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] It is actually very impressive to see the amount of aircraft overflight around the rural subsistence, because the activity is increasing significantly and they have reached a median of 12 overflights per day near human development, which is six times greater than undeveloped areas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Therefore, those planes startle caribou prefer to avoid aircraft themselves, which has a result that they will need to go farther to do a better harvest, but this will occur in adding some costs for fuel, equipment, and the effort for sure.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Those kind of examples help to understand the impact on social-ecological dynamics in Antarctica.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The ambient noise present within the world's oceans; geophonic, anthrophonic, and biophonic, has been identified as a critical indicator to the well-being of the regional biosphere.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The acoustic niche hypothesis, as proposed by acoustic ecologist Bernie Krause in 1993, refers to the process in which organisms partition the acoustic domain, finding their own niche in frequency and/or time in order to communicate without competition from other species.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The theory draws from the ideas of niche differentiation and can be used to predict differences between young and mature ecosystems.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Similar to how interspecific competition can place limits on the number of coexisting species that can utilize a given availability of habitats or resources, the available acoustic space in an environment is a limited resource that is partitioned among those species competing to utilize it.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] In mature ecosystems, species will sing at unique bandwidths and specific times, displaying a lack of interspecies competition in the acoustic environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Conversely, in young ecosystems, one is more likely to encounter multiple species using similar frequency bandwidths, which can result in interference between their respective calls, or a complete lack of activity in uncontested bandwidths.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Biological invasions can also result in interference in the acoustic niche, with non-native species altering the dynamics of the native community by producing signals that mask or degrade native signals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] This can cause a variety of ecological impacts, such as decreased reproduction, aggressive interactions, and altered predator-prey dynamics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] The degree of partitioning in an environment can be used to indicate ecosystem health and biodiversity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] "Dominion" uses Canadian soundmarks that were made in different province by the World Soundscape Project at Simon Fraser University for an event of cross-country tour that happened in 1973.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] What is interesting about those sounds is that they are stretched over the time, so the extended versions allowed the people that listen to the sound in a more harmonic way.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Those unique sound signals, were picked up by the live performers and then amplified to give the best experience possible to his audience.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] This is a subfield of archeology and acoustics that in general study the relation between people and sound along the history.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] This is an interdisciplinary field that has methodological contributions from acoustics, archeology and computer simulation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Many cultures explored through archaeology were mostly focused on the oral, which lead the researchers to believe that studying the sonic nature of archaeological sites and artifacts may reveal new information on the civilization being scrutinized.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] Moglen (2007) recreated pre-historical Soundscapes (Acoustic Ecology) at University of California, Berkeley's Department of Anthropology, combining compositional techniques with site recordings for a non-diegetic piece in the virtual world of Second Life, on "Okapi Island" .
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/acoustic-ecology] At the Center for New Media the acoustic ecological setting of the former jazz scene in Oakland, CA was developed for a virtual world setting.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Born in Kirkcaldy, Fife, he studied social philosophy at the University of Glasgow and at the University of Oxford, where he was one of the only students to benefit from scholarships set up by John Snell.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Following his graduation, he delivered a successful series of public lectures at the University of Edinburgh, that met with acclaim.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] This led to a collaboration with David Hume during the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith obtained a professorship at Glasgow, where he taught moral philosophy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] During this period, he wrote and published *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Subsequently, he assumed a tutoring position that facilitated travel throughout Europe, where he encountered intellectual figures of his era.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In response to the prevailing policy of safeguarding national markets and merchants through the reduction of imports and the augmentation of exports, a practice that came to be known as mercantilism, Smith laid the foundational principles of classical free-market economic theory.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] *The Wealth of Nations* was a precursor to the modern academic discipline of economics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In this and other works, he developed the concept of division of labour and expounded upon how rational self-interest and competition can lead to economic prosperity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith was controversial in his day and his general approach and writing style were often satirised by writers such as Horace Walpole.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Adam Smith was born in Kirkcaldy, in Fife, Scotland.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] His father, Adam Smith senior, was a Scottish Writer to the Signet (senior solicitor), advocate and prosecutor (judge advocate) and also served as comptroller of the customs in Kirkcaldy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's mother was born Margaret Douglas, daughter of the landed Robert Douglas of Strathendry, also in Fife; she married Smith's father in 1720.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Two months before Smith was born, his father died, leaving his mother a widow.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The date of Smith's baptism into the Church of Scotland at Kirkcaldy was 5 June 1723 and this has often been treated as if it were also his date of birth, which is unknown.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Although few events in Smith's early childhood are known, the Scottish journalist John Rae, a biographer of Smith, recorded that Smith was abducted by Romani at the age of three and released when others went to rescue him.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith was close to his mother, who probably encouraged him to pursue his scholarly ambitions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith entered the University of Glasgow at age 14 and studied moral philosophy under Francis Hutcheson.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Here he developed his passion for the philosophical concepts of reason, civilian liberties and the freedom of speech.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1740 he was the graduate scholar presented to undertake postgraduate studies at the Balliol College of the University of Oxford, under the Snell Exhibition.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith considered the teaching at Glasgow to be far superior to that at Oxford, which he found intellectually stifling.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] According to William Robert Scott, "The Oxford of [Smith's] time gave little if any help towards what was to be his lifework." Nevertheless, he took the opportunity while at Oxford to teach himself several subjects by reading many books from the shelves of the large Bodleian Library.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] When Smith was not studying on his own, his time at Oxford was not a happy one, according to his letters.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Near the end of his time there, he began suffering from shaking fits, probably the symptoms of a nervous breakdown.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He left Oxford in 1746, before his scholarship ended.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's curriculum at Glasgow included logic, metaphysics, moral philosophy, and natural philosophy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Under Hutcheson, Smith debated questions of natural justice, fair exchange, and the moral dimensions of commerce; themes which would be reflected in *The Wealth of Nations*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Hutcheson argued that workers deserved compensation sufficient to sustain themselves and their families, a concept Smith would later develop into his broader theory of natural wage levels.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In Book V of *The Wealth of Nations*, Smith comments on the low quality of instruction and the meager intellectual activity at English universities, when compared to their Scottish counterparts.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith began delivering public lectures in 1748 at the University of Edinburgh, sponsored by the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh under the patronage of Lord Kames.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] His lecture topics included rhetoric and *belles-lettres*, and later the subject of "the progress of opulence".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] On this latter topic, he first expounded his economic philosophy of "the obvious and simple system of natural liberty".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] While Smith was not adept at public speaking, his lectures met with success.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1750 Smith met the philosopher David Hume, who was his senior by more than a decade.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In their writings covering history, politics, philosophy, economics, and religion, Smith and Hume shared closer intellectual and personal bonds than with other important figures of the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1751 Smith earned a professorship at Glasgow teaching logic courses, and in 1752, he was elected a member of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh, having been introduced to the society by Henry Home, Lord Kames.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The following year, when the position of head of Moral Philosophy in Glasgow became vacant, Smith took over the role.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He worked as an academic for the next 13 years, which he characterised as "by far the most useful and therefore by far the happiest and most honorable period [of his life]".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith published *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* in 1759, embodying some of his Glasgow lectures.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] This work was concerned with how human morality depends on sympathy between agent and spectator, or the individual and other members of society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith defined "mutual sympathy" as the basis of moral sentiments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Following the publication of *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, Smith became so popular that many wealthy students left their schools in other countries to enroll at Glasgow to learn under Smith.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] At this time, Smith began to give more attention to jurisprudence and economics in his lectures and less to his theories of morals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] For example, Smith lectured that the cause of increase in national wealth is labour, rather than the nation's quantity of gold or silver, which is the basis for mercantilism, the economic theory that dominated Western European economic policies at the time.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1762, the University of Glasgow conferred on Smith the title of Doctor of Laws (LL.D.).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] At the end of 1763, he obtained an offer from the chancellor of the exchequer, Charles Townshend—who had been introduced to Smith by David Hume—to tutor his stepson, Henry Scott, the young Duke of Buccleuch as preparation for a career in international politics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith resigned from his professorship in 1764 to take the tutoring position.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He subsequently attempted to return the fees he had collected from his students because he had resigned partway through the term, but his students refused.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's tutoring job entailed touring Europe with Scott, during which time he educated Scott on a variety of subjects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He was paid £300 per year (plus expenses) along with a £300-per-year pension; roughly twice his former income as a teacher.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith first travelled as a tutor to Toulouse, France, where he stayed for a year and a half.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] According to his own account, he found Toulouse to be somewhat boring, having written to Hume that he "had begun to write a book to pass away the time".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] After touring the south of France the group moved to Geneva, where Smith met the French writer and philosopher Voltaire.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In Paris Smith encountered the Physiocracy school founded by François Quesnay and conversed with their intellectuals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Physiocrats were opposed to mercantilism, the dominating economic theory of the time, illustrated in their motto *Laissez faire et laissez passer, le monde va de lui même!* (Let do and let pass, the world goes on by itself!).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The wealth of France had been virtually depleted by Louis XIV and Louis XV in ruinous wars, and was further exhausted in aiding the American revolutionary soldiers, against the British.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1766 Henry Scott's younger brother died in Paris, and Smith's tour as a tutor ended shortly thereafter.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith returned home that year to Kirkcaldy, and he devoted much of the next decade to writing his *magnum opus*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] There, he befriended Henry Moyes, a young blind man who showed precocious aptitude.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith secured the patronage of David Hume and Thomas Reid in the young man's education.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In May 1767 Smith was elected fellow of the Royal Society of London, and was elected a member of the Literary Club in 1775.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] *The Wealth of Nations* was published in 1776 and was an instant success, selling out its first edition in only six months.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1778 Smith was appointed to a post as commissioner of customs in Scotland and went to live with his mother (who died in 1784) in Panmure House in the Canongate in Edinburgh.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Five years later, as a member of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh when it received its royal charter, he automatically became one of the founding members of the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] From 1787 to 1789 he occupied the honorary position of Lord Rector of the University of Glasgow.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith died in the northern wing of Panmure House in Edinburgh on 17 July 1790 after a painful illness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] His body was buried in the Canongate Kirkyard.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] On his deathbed, Smith expressed disappointment that he had not achieved more.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's literary executors were two friends from the Scottish academic world: the physicist and chemist Joseph Black and the pioneering geologist James Hutton.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith left behind many notes and some unpublished material, but gave instructions to destroy anything that was not fit for publication.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He mentioned an early unpublished *History of Astronomy* as probably suitable, and it duly appeared in 1795, along with other material such as *Essays on Philosophical Subjects*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's library went by his will to David Douglas, Lord Reston (son of his cousin Colonel Robert Douglas of Strathendry, Fife), who lived with Smith.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] It was eventually divided between Douglas's two surviving children, Cecilia Margaret (Mrs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] On the death in 1878 of her husband, the Reverend W.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The remainder passed to her son, Professor Robert Oliver Cunningham of Queen's College, Belfast, who presented a part to the library of Queen's College.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] After his death, the remaining books were sold.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Bannerman in 1879, her portion of the library went intact to the New College (of the Free Church) in Edinburgh and the collection was transferred to the University of Edinburgh Main Library in 1972.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Not much is known about Smith's personal views beyond what can be deduced from his published articles.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] His personal papers were destroyed after his death, per his request.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He never married, and seems to have maintained a close relationship with his mother, with whom he lived after his return from France and who died six years before him.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith was described by several of his contemporaries and biographers as comically absent-minded, with peculiar habits of speech and gait, and a smile of "inexpressible benignity".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He was known to talk to himself, a habit that began during his childhood when he would smile in rapt conversation with invisible companions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He also had occasional spells of imaginary illness, and he is reported to have had books and papers placed in tall stacks in his study.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] According to one story, Smith took Charles Townshend on a tour of a tanning factory, and while discussing free trade, Smith walked into a huge tanning pit from which he needed help to escape.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He is also said to have put bread and butter into a teapot, drunk the concoction, and declared it to be the worst cup of tea he had ever had.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] According to another account, Smith distractedly went out walking in his nightgown and ended up 15 miles (24 km) outside town, before nearby church bells brought him back to reality.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] James Boswell, who was a student of Smith's at Glasgow University, and later knew him at the Literary Club, says that Smith thought that speaking about his ideas in conversation might reduce the sale of his books, so his conversation was unimpressive.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] According to Boswell, he once told Sir Joshua Reynolds, that "he made it a rule when in company never to talk of what he understood".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith has been alternatively described as someone who "had a large nose, bulging eyes, a protruding lower lip, a nervous twitch, and a speech impediment" and one whose "countenance was manly and agreeable".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith is said to have acknowledged his looks at one point, saying, "I am a beau in nothing but my books." Smith rarely sat for portraits, so almost all depictions of him created during his lifetime were drawn from memory.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The best-known portraits of Smith are the profile by James Tassie and two etchings by John Kay.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The line engravings produced for the covers of 19th-century reprints of *The Wealth of Nations* were based largely on Tassie's medallion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Considerable scholarly debate has occurred about the nature of Smith's religious views.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] His father had shown a strong interest in Christianity and belonged to the moderate wing of the Church of Scotland, and the fact that he received the Snell Exhibition suggests that he may have gone to Oxford with the intention of pursuing a career in the Church of England.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The British economist Ronald Coase challenged the view that Smith was a deist, based on the fact that Smith's writings never explicitly invoke God as an explanation of the harmonies of the natural or the human worlds.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Philosophy afterwards endeavoured to account for them, from more familiar causes, or from such as mankind were better acquainted with than the agency of the gods".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Some authors argue that Smith's social and economic philosophy is inherently theological and that his entire model of social order is logically dependent on the notion of God's action in nature.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Brendan Long argues that Smith was a theist, whereas according to Gavin Kennedy, Smith was "in some sense" a Christian.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith was also a close friend of David Hume, who, despite debate about his religious views in modern scholarship, was commonly characterised in his own time as an atheist.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The publication in 1777 of Smith's letter to William Strahan, in which he described Hume's courage in the face of death in spite of his irreligiosity, attracted considerable controversy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In 1759 Smith published his first work, *The Theory of Moral Sentiments,* sold by the co-publishers Andrew Millar of London and Alexander Kincaid of Edinburgh.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith continued making extensive revisions to the book until his death.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Although *The Wealth of Nations* is widely regarded as Smith's most influential work, Smith himself is believed to have considered *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* to be a superior work.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith proposes a theory of sympathy, in which the act of observing others and seeing the judgements they form of both others and oneself makes people aware of themselves and how others perceive their behaviour.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The feedback received by an individual from perceiving (or imagining) others' judgement creates an incentive to achieve "mutual sympathy of sentiments" with them and leads people to develop habits, and then principles, of behaviour, which come to constitute one's conscience.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] While scholars have historically recognised a conflict - often phrased the "Adam Smith Problem"-between the exaggeration on sympathy in *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and self-interest in *The Wealth of Nations*, modern scholarship largely overlooks this contradiction.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Instead the two works are widely seen as part of a unified system of moral and economic philosophy that are able to co-exist and complement each other.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] These scholars contend that in *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, Smith develops a theory of psychology in which individuals seek the approval of the "impartial spectator" as a result of a natural desire to have outside observers sympathise with their sentiments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Rather than viewing *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and *The Wealth of Nations* as presenting incompatible views of human nature, some Smith scholars regard the works as emphasising different aspects of human nature that vary depending on the situation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In the first part – *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* – he laid down the foundation of his vision of humanity and society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In the second – *The Wealth of Nations* – he elaborated on the virtue of prudence, which for him meant the relations between people in the private sphere of the economy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] It was his plan to further elaborate on the virtue of justice in the third book.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] James Otteson argues that both books are Newtonian in their methodology and deploy a similar "market model" for explaining the creation and development of large-scale human social orders, including morality, economics, as well as language.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Disagreement exists between classical and neoclassical economists about the central message of Smith's most influential work: *An Inquiry into the Nature and Causes of the Wealth of Nations* (1776).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He elaborated on the virtue of prudence, which for him meant the relations between people in the private sphere of the economy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] He planned to further elaborate on the virtue of justice in the third book.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith used the term "the invisible hand" in "History of Astronomy" referring to "the invisible hand of Jupiter", and once in each of his *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* (1759) and *The Wealth of Nations* (1776).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] This last statement about "an invisible hand" has been interpreted in numerous ways.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In relation to Bernard Mandeville's contention that "Private Vices ... may be turned into Public Benefits", Smith's belief that when an individual pursues his self-interest under conditions of justice, he unintentionally promotes the good of society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Self-interested competition in the free market, he argued, would tend to benefit society as a whole by keeping prices low, while still building in an incentive for a wide variety of goods and services.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith states that the interest of manufacturers and merchants "in any particular branch of trade or manufactures, is always in some respects different from, and even opposite to, that of the public ...
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The neoclassical interest in Smith's statement about "an invisible hand" originates in the possibility of seeing it as a precursor of neoclassical economics and its concept of general equilibrium; Paul Samuelson's "Economics" refers six times to Smith's "invisible hand".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] To emphasise this connection, Samuelson quotes Smith's "invisible hand" statement substituting "general interest" for "public interest".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Samuelson concludes: "Smith was unable to prove the essence of his invisible-hand doctrine.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Conversely, classical economists see in Smith's first sentences his programme to promote "The Wealth of Nations".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Using the physiocratical concept of the economy as a circular process, to secure growth the inputs of Period 2 must exceed the inputs of Period 1.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Therefore, those outputs of Period 1 which are not used or usable as inputs of Period 2 are regarded as unproductive labour, as they do not contribute to growth.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] This is what Smith had heard in France from, among others, François Quesnay, whose ideas Smith was so impressed by that he might have dedicated *The Wealth of Nations* to him had he not died beforehand.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] To this French insight that unproductive labour should be reduced to use labour more productively, Smith added his own proposal, that productive labour should be made even more productive by deepening the division of labour.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith argued that deepening the division of labour under competition leads to greater productivity, which leads to lower prices and thus an increasing standard of living—"general plenty" and "universal opulence"—for all.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Extended markets and increased production lead to the continuous reorganisation of production and the invention of new ways of producing, which in turn lead to further increased production, lower prices, and improved standards of living.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's central message is, therefore, that under dynamic competition, a growth machine secures "The Wealth of Nations".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith's argument predicted Britain's evolution as the workshop of the world, underselling and outproducing all its competitors.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] According to Smith, "It is not very unreasonable that the rich should contribute to the public expense, not only in proportion to their revenue, but something more in that proportion".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Smith wrote that a government is duty-bound to provide public services that "support the whole of society" like provide public education, transportation, national defence, a justice system, public safety, and public infrastructure to support commerce.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Shortly before his death, Smith had nearly all his manuscripts destroyed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] In his last years, he seemed to have been planning two major treatises, one on the theory and history of law and one on the sciences and arts.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] The posthumously published *Essays on Philosophical Subjects*, a history of astronomy down to Smith's own era, plus some thoughts on ancient physics and metaphysics, probably contain parts of what would have been the latter treatise.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] *Lectures on Jurisprudence* were notes taken from Smith's early lectures, plus an early draft of *The Wealth of Nations*, published as part of the 1976 Glasgow Edition of the works and correspondence of Smith.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p01] Other works, including some published posthumously, include *Lectures on Justice, Police, Revenue, and Arms* (1763) (first published in 1896); and *Essays on Philosophical Subjects* (1795).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] In light of the arguments put forward by Smith and other economic theorists in Britain, academic belief in mercantilism began to decline in Britain in the late 18th century.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] During the Industrial Revolution, Britain embraced free trade and Smith's *laissez-faire* economics, and via the British Empire, used its power to spread a broadly liberal economic model around the world, characterised by open markets, and relatively barrier-free domestic and international trade.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] George Stigler attributes to Smith "the most important substantive proposition in all of economics".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] It is that, under competition, owners of resources (for example labour, land, and capital) will use them most profitably, resulting in an equal rate of return in equilibrium for all uses, adjusted for apparent differences arising from such factors as training, trust, hardship, and unemployment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Paul Samuelson finds in Smith's pluralist use of supply and demand as applied to wages, rents, and profit a valid and valuable anticipation of the general equilibrium modelling of Léon Walras a century later.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith's allowance for wage increases in the short and intermediate term from capital accumulation and invention contrasted with Thomas Robert Malthus, David Ricardo, and Karl Marx in their propounding a rigid subsistence–wage theory of labour supply.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Joseph Schumpeter criticised Smith for a lack of technical rigour, yet he argued that this enabled Smith's writings to appeal to wider audiences: "His very limitation made for success.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Had he been more brilliant, he would not have been taken so seriously.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Had he dug more deeply, had he unearthed more recondite truth, had he used more difficult and ingenious methods, he would not have been understood.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] But he had no such ambitions; in fact he disliked whatever went beyond plain common sense.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He never moved above the heads of even the dullest readers.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Classical economists presented competing theories to those of Smith, termed the "labour theory of value".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Later Marxian economics descending from classical economics also use Smith's labour theories, in part.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The first volume of Marx's major work, *Das Kapital*, was published in German in 1867.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] In it Marx focused on the labour theory of value and what he considered to be the exploitation of labour by capital.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The labour theory of value held that the value of a thing was determined by the labour that went into its production.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] This contrasts with the modern contention of neoclassical economics, that the value of a thing is determined by what one is willing to give up to obtain the thing.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Frédéric Bastiat advocated a similar theory, that the value of a thing or service was its utility, or usefulness, to others.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] One example he used was of one finding a large diamond after having done little labor; yet it was still valuable because others wanted it.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The body of theory later termed "neoclassical economics" or "marginalism" formed from about 1870 to 1910.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The term "economics" was popularised by such neoclassical economists as Alfred Marshall as a concise synonym for "economic science" and a substitute for the earlier, broader term "political economy" used by Smith.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] This corresponded to the influence on the subject of mathematical methods used in the natural sciences.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Neoclassical economics systematised supply and demand as joint determinants of price and quantity in market equilibrium, affecting both the allocation of output and the distribution of income.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] It dispensed with the labour theory of value of which Smith was most famously identified with in classical economics, in favour of a marginal utility theory of value on the demand side and a more general theory of costs on the supply side.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The bicentennial anniversary of the publication of *The Wealth of Nations* was celebrated in 1976, resulting in increased interest for *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and his other works throughout academia.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] After 1976 Smith was more likely to be represented as the author of both *The Wealth of Nations* and *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, and thereby as the founder of a moral philosophy and the science of economics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] His *homo economicus* or "economic man" was also more often represented as a moral person.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Additionally, economists David Levy and Sandra Peart in "The Secret History of the Dismal Science" point to his opposition to hierarchy and beliefs in equality, including racial equality, and provide additional support for those who point to Smith's opposition to slavery, colonialism, and empire.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Emphasised also are Smith's statements of the need for high wages for the poor, and the efforts to keep wages low.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] They also cite Smith's opposition to the often expressed view that science is superior to common sense.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He challenged ideas that colonies were key to British prosperity and power.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He rejected that other cultures, such as China and India, were culturally and developmentally inferior to Europe.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] While he favoured "commercial society", he did not support radical social change and the imposition of commercial society on other societies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He proposed that colonies be given independence or that full political rights be extended to colonial subjects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith's chapter on colonies, in turn, would help shape British imperial debates from the mid-19th century onward.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] *The Wealth of Nations* would become an ambiguous text regarding the imperial question.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] In his chapter on colonies, Smith pondered how to solve the crisis developing across the Atlantic among the empire's 13 American colonies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He offered two different proposals for easing tensions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The first proposal called for giving the colonies their independence, and by thus parting on a friendly basis, Britain would be able to develop and maintain a free-trade relationship with them, and possibly even an informal military alliance.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith's second proposal called for a theoretical imperial federation that would bring the colonies and the metropole closer together through an imperial parliamentary system and imperial free trade.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith's most prominent disciple in 19th-century Britain, the peace-advocate Richard Cobden, preferred the first proposal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Cobden would lead the Anti-Corn Law League in overturning the Corn Laws in 1846, shifting Britain to a policy of free trade and empire "on the cheap" for decades to come.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] This hands-off approach toward the British Empire would become known as Cobdenism or the Manchester School.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] By the turn of the century, however, advocates of Smith's second proposal such as Joseph Shield Nicholson would become ever more vocal in opposing Cobdenism, calling instead for imperial federation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] As Marc-William Palen notes: "On the one hand, Adam Smith's late nineteenth and early twentieth-century Cobdenite adherents used his theories to argue for gradual imperial devolution and empire 'on the cheap'.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Between 1867 and 1870, a statue of Smith was built into the outside wall of 6 Burlington Gardens, then the headquarters of the University of London (now home to the Royal Academy of Arts).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] A large-scale memorial of Smith by Alexander Stoddart was unveiled on 4 July 2008 in Edinburgh.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] It is a 10-foot (3.0 m)-tall bronze sculpture and it stands above the Royal Mile outside St Giles' Cathedral in Parliament Square, near the Mercat cross.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Sculptor Jim Sanborn has created multiple pieces which feature Smith's work.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] At Central Connecticut State University is *Circulating Capital*, a tall cylinder which features an extract from *The Wealth of Nations* on the lower half, and on the upper half, some of the same text, but represented in binary code.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] At the University of North Carolina at Charlotte, outside the Belk College of Business Administration, is *Adam Smith's Spinning Top*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Another Smith sculpture is at Cleveland State University.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] A bust of Smith is in the Hall of Heroes of the National Wallace Monument in Stirling.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Five paving stones, displaying quotations from Smith's works, were unveiled in December 2023 on High Street in Glasgow.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] They were commissioned by the University of Glasgow to mark the 300th anniversary of Smith's birth.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Adam Smith resided at Panmure House from 1778 to 1790.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] In 2008, the house was purchased by the Edinburgh Business School at Heriot-Watt University and funds were raised for its restoration.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] In 2018 it was formally opened as a study centre in Smith's honour.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Other writers have argued that Smith's support for *laissez-faire* (which in French means leave alone) has been overstated.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Herbert Stein wrote that the people who "wear an Adam Smith necktie" do it to "make a statement of their devotion to the idea of free markets and limited government", and that this misrepresents Smith's ideas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Stein writes that Smith "was not pure or doctrinaire about this idea.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He viewed government intervention in the market with great skepticism...yet he was prepared to accept or propose qualifications to that policy in the specific cases where he judged that their net effect would be beneficial and would not undermine the basically free character of the system.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He did not wear the Adam Smith necktie." In Stein's reading, *The Wealth of Nations* could justify the Food and Drug Administration, the Consumer Product Safety Commission, mandatory employer health benefits, environmentalism, and "discriminatory taxation to deter improper or luxurious behavior".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Some commentators have argued that Smith's works show support for a progressive, not flat, income tax and that he specifically named taxes that he thought should be required by the state, among them luxury-goods taxes and tax on rent.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Yet Smith argued for the "impossibility of taxing the people, in proportion to their economic revenue, by any capitation".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith argued that taxes should principally go toward protecting "justice" and "certain publick institutions" that were necessary for the benefit of all of society, which could not be adequately provided by private enterprise.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Additionally, Smith outlined the proper expenses of the government in *The Wealth of Nations, Book V, Ch.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Included in his requirements of a government is to enforce contracts and provide justice system, grant patents and copy rights, provide public goods such as infrastructure, provide national defence, and regulate banking.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The role of the government was to provide goods "of such a nature that the profit could never repay the expense to any individual" such as roads, bridges, canals, and harbours.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He also encouraged invention and new ideas through his patent enforcement and support of infant industry monopolies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He supported partial public subsidies for elementary education, and he believed that competition among religious institutions would provide general benefit to the society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Finally, he outlined how the government should support the dignity of the monarch or chief magistrate, such that they are equal or above the public in fashion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] He further stated that monarchs should be provided for in a greater fashion than magistrates of a republic because "we naturally expect more splendor in the court of a king than in the mansion-house of a doge".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] However, he added that in general, a retaliatory tariff "seems a bad method of compensating the injury done to certain classes of our people, to do another injury ourselves, not only to those classes, but to almost all the other classes of them".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Economic historians such as Jacob Viner regard Smith as a strong advocate of free markets and limited government (what Smith called "natural liberty"), but not as a dogmatic supporter of *laissez-faire*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The economist Daniel Klein believes using the term "free-market economics" or "free-market economist" to identify the ideas of Smith is too general and slightly misleading.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Klein offers six characteristics central to the identity of Smith's economic thought and argues that a new name is needed to give a more accurate depiction of the "Smithian" identity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] The economist David Ricardo set straight some of the misunderstandings about Smith's thoughts on free market.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Many continue to fall victim to the thinking that Smith was a free-market economist without exception, though he was not.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Ricardo pointed out that Smith was in support of helping infant industries.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith believed that the government should subsidise newly formed industry, but he did fear that when the infant industry grew into adulthood, it would be unwilling to surrender the government help.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith also supported tariffs on imported goods to counteract an internal tax on the same good.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Smith also fell to pressure in supporting some tariffs in support for national defence.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/adam-smith-p02] Some have also argued, Emma Rothschild among them, that Smith would have supported a minimum wage, although no direct textual evidence supports the claim.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The **environmental history of the United States** covers the history of the environment over the centuries to the late 20th century, plus the political and expert debates on conservation and environmental issues.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The term "conservation" appeared in 1908 and was gradually replaced by "environmentalism" in the 1970s as the focus shifted from managing and protecting natural resources to a broader concern for the environment as a whole and the negative impact of poor air or water on humans.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The late twentieth century saw a shift towards “environmental justice,” highlighting the way in which environmental benefits and burdens are unevenly distributed across lines of race, class, and ethnicity.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] For recent history see Environmental policy of the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to Erin Stewart Mauldin, the geological history of the United States predates human settlement by millions of years.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The landscape of the North American continent's landscape was shaped by plate tectonics, volcanic activity, and glaciation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Appalachian Mountains resulted from plate collisions, the Rocky Mountains from the subduction of the Pacific Ocean floor, and the Pacific Northwest and New England from the accretion of microcontinents.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Glaciation formed the Great Lakes and influenced soil composition across the country, with volcanic activity contributing to regions like the Columbia Plateau.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Paleoindians from Siberia were the continent's first human inhabitants starting 30,000 BCE.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] They coexisted with megafauna like mammoths.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The reasons for these species' extinction, possibly due to climate change or human hunting, remain debated.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The absence of large domesticable animals in North America affected the development of societies, limiting hunting and herding and later giving European colonizers a biological edge.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Native Americans developed diverse subsistence strategies, including agriculture, hunting, and fishing, with varying practices across regions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] They also impacted the landscape through land clearing and hunting practices, leading to environmental changes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The pre-Columbian landscape encountered by Europeans was significantly shaped by human activity, challenging the idea of an untouched wilderness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Scholar Dina Gilio-Whitaker explains that as the Spanish arrived in North America in the 1500s, and the English established the first permanent colony of Jamestown in 1607, they brought ideas of land ownership that conflicted with the Indigenous attitude of land as a commune.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The settler colonial drive to own the land required the forced removal of Indigenous people.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] European settlers destroyed Indigenous agricultural resources in a successful attempt to starve people off their ancestral land.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The disruption and seizure of Indigenous trade routes made some native groups vulnerable and dependent on the settlers themselves.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These actions altered the environment away from that which was stewarded by native peoples, instead shifting it towards colonial ideas of ownership.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to historian David Silkenat, indigenous practices and stewardship such as controlled burns, subsistence hunting and gathering, and large farms growing corn, beans, squash, and more, were met with settler monoculture plantations dependent on enslaved people.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Settler agriculture in the South varied, with a mixture of smaller farms and large extractive plantations which took a toll on the soils.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] However, settlers did not easily adapt to their new environment, finding that European farming practices did not translate to their new land according to historian Kenneth MacMillan.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] While the English expected the climate of the Carolinas and Virginia to be like that of Spain, they were met with both hotter and colder conditions than expected.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] They mistakenly believed there to be similar commodities to that of the East and West Indies such as gold.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Jamestown colony, located in what is now Virginia, facing the inconsistent weather of the South, struggled to establish reliable food sources, often having to trade with native people for corn and other resources, especially through the cold winters.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] However, by 1617, English tobacco was established as a cash crop, and grown on plantations, using African slave labor.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Before 1815 the New England farmers were largely self-sufficient.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The forest provided wood to build homes and barns, and fueled the stove all winter long.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Timber was sold for ship construction and naval stores were sold for export to England.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The remaining forest was the habitat for deer and other game that were easily hunted with muskets or traps.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Once cleared the land provided pasture for the sheep (raised for the wool), the hogs, and the family cow, as well as space for the vegetable garden.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The significance of the forest ranged from a threat to settlers to being a place of Puritan religious significance, as well as a source of beauty and pride.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As population grew the forest transitioned from a perceived abundance to a dwindling asset.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] After 1815, when export markets reopened after the Napoleonic Wars and the War of 1812, farmers in the region increasingly focused more on profitable commercial crops, especially sheep, cattle, hay, lumber, wheat.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As the nearby cities grew they sold more milk and cheese, eggs, apples, cranberries and maple syrup.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to geographer Michael Williams, by 1860, about 153 million acres of forest had been cleared for farms, and another 11 million acres cut down by industrial logging, mining, railroad construction, and urban expansion.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] A fourth of the original forest cover in the eastern states was gone.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] At the same time there was a major change in how Americans viewed forests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] They were recognized as the foundation of industrialization, agricultural expansion, and material progress.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Lumber was the nation's largest industry in 1850, and second in 1860 behind textiles.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As Frederick Starr emphasized in 1865, forests were integral to the four key necessities for prosperity: "cheap bread, cheap houses, cheap fuel, and cheap transportation for passengers and freights." Lumbering was a very dangerous trade, with crippling accidents and death a common hazard.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] But it paid well because the lumber was essential for construction and wood was the main fuel for homes, business, steamboats and railroads.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Intellectuals began examining the complex relationships between forests and soil, climate, farming, railroading and the economy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] They pondered the overall ecological balance.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Was the nation's energy at risk as settlement expanded westward into the trans-Mississippi prairies where wood was scarce.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Given the economic and cultural importance of the forests, some worried commentators, especially George Perkins Marsh and Increase Lapham. began questioning the widespread destruction.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] They saw the forests and backwoods pioneers as symbols of America, and their disappearance was concerning.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Romantic writers such as Henry David Thoreau and Ralph Waldo Emerson helped Americans appreciate the aesthetic and recreational value of forests, beyond just their economic importance.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The early conservation movement had its roots in these concerns.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, wastes from mining operations began to enter rivers and streams, and iron bloomeries and furnaces used water for cooling.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In the early 19th century, the development of steam engines led to their use in the mining and manufacturing sectors (such as textiles).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The expanded use of steam engines generated larger volumes of heated water (thermal pollution).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The productivity gains, along with the introduction of railroads in the 1830s and 1840s—which increased the overall demand for coal and minerals—led to additional generation of wastes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Second Industrial Revolution led to development of manufacturing processes that generated new types of wastes, including air, water and land pollution (solid and hazardous waste).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Cash wages brought rural workers into the new textile mills first in New England after 1810 and then in the South after 1870.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The mills were powered by waterwheels on local rivers and caused little harm to the external environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The hazards came indoors as workers faced air and noise pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The men, women and children worked in family teams 10 hours a day in a tightly enclosed environment filled with dust and fiber.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The machinery occasionally caused accidents but the polluted environment was much more serious.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Having large numbers of people laboring in close quarters day after day was the ideal settings for the rapid spread of diseases including the common cold, bronchitis, pneumonia and tuberculosis.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The also suffered hearing loss and fatigue.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Byssinosis, also known as "brown lung disease" or "Monday fever," was particularly prevalent among cotton textile workers, with symptoms including chest tightness and shortness of breath..
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] There were sharp disagreements among workers, employers, and medical professionals regarding the impact of factory environments on health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The mills seldom employed medical care on site but they did support community hospitals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Underground mining was a very hazardous occupation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] However the coal, iron, lead and copper was essential for industrialization.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Enslaved people worked the mines pre-civil war.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Later, labor demand drew many European immigrants, black workers under Jim Crow, and local Appalachian families.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to economic historian Price V.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Fishback, in addition to the hazards of mine collapses, miners and the area where mines, such as coal, were located faced well and water supply contamination.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] From various mining processes, arsenic, barium, lead, manganese, iron, and sulfate, were found in well and water supplies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Open mine fields, blasting, and transportation also created particulate matter and fumes containing sulfur dioxide, nitrous oxide, benzene, carbon monoxide, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, arsenic, mercury, and other heavy metals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In turn, miners and those who lived near the mines face black lung, cardiovascular diseases, other lung diseases, and potentially cancer.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Paul Rakes examines coal mine fatalities in West Virginia in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Besides the well-publicized mine disasters that killed a number of miners at a time, there were many smaller episodes in which one or two miners lost their lives.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Mine accidents were considered inevitable, and mine safety did not appreciably improve the situation because of lax enforcement.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] West Virginia's mines were considered so unsafe that immigration officials would not recommend them as a source of employment for immigrants, but they came anyway for the high pay.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] When the United States Bureau of Mines was given more authority to regulate mine safety in the 1960s, safety awareness improved, and West Virginia coal mines became less dangerous.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The transition after 1920 from coal to hydro and oil and later to nuclear, gas and solar power dramatically lowered the hazards to energy workers.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Likewise the transition from underground to surface mining.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The British government attempt to restrict westward expansion with the ineffective Proclamation Line of 1763 was cancelled by the new United States government.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The first major movement west of the Appalachian Mountains began in Pennsylvania, Virginia and North Carolina as soon as the Revolutionary War was effectively won in 1781.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Pioneers housed themselves in a rough lean-to or at most a one-room log cabin.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The main food supply at first came from hunting deer, turkeys, and other abundant small game.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In 1788, American pioneers to the Northwest Territory established Marietta, Ohio as the first permanent American settlement in the Northwest Territory.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Louisiana Purchase of 1803 doubled the size of the nation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] It contained a few small European settlements and large numbers of Native Americans.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The federal government had charge of Indian affairs, and one by one purchased Indian lands.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Individuals who were willing to assimilate into American society were allowed to remain.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Tribes that wanted to keep their self-government kept a small part of their land as an Indian reservation and sold the rest to the federal government for an annual subsidy from the Bureau of Indian Affairs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Those tribes east of the Mississippi were usually relocated further west, primarily to Indian Territory (now the state of Oklahoma).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As settlers spread Westward, their desire to commodify the land conflicted with the existence of Native peoples in those regions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In turn, military campaigns were utilized for forced removal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Some examples of this were long marches off land to reservations or prison camps at gunpoint such as the Long Walk of the Diné in 1864 and the Trail of Tears for the Cherokee, Creek, Chickasaw, Seminole, and Choctaw from 1838 to 1839.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Removals led to the deaths of over 25 percent of those forced to march and the loss of life-sustaining livestock and crops.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] For some people, their new lands resembled those they left behind and were able to adapt to new environments while altering their way of lives to fit the infrastructure of American expansion that spread into the West and onto their land such as railroads.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] However, during the Diné's forced walk to the first reservation in the West, many died before and after arriving.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The land provided was overpopulated with brackish water and an inadequate amount of firewood.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Despite attempts to continue farming practices, both the irrigation system and crops failed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] By 1813, the western frontier had reached the Mississippi River.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Louis, Missouri was the largest town on the frontier, the gateway for travel westward, and a principal trading center for Mississippi River traffic and inland commerce.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] There was wide agreement on the need to settle the new territories quickly, but the debate polarized over the price the government should charge.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The conservatives and Whigs, typified by president John Quincy Adams, wanted a moderated pace that charged the newcomers enough to pay the costs of the federal government.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Democrats, however, tolerated a wild scramble for land at very low prices.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The final resolution came in the Homestead Law of 1862, with a moderated pace that gave settlers 160 acres free after they worked on it for five years.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] From the 1770s to the 1830s, pioneers moved into the new lands that stretched from Kentucky to Alabama to Texas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Most had operated farmers back east and now relocated in family groups.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Hacker shows how wasteful the first generation of pioneers was; they were too ignorant to cultivate the land properly and when the natural fertility of virgin land was used up, they sold out and moved west to try again.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Hacker adds that the second wave of settlers reclaimed the land, repaired the damage, and practiced a more sustainable agriculture.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As European colonists settled in what would become the United States, they established large extractive plantations for crops such as tobacco, rice, and cotton, relying on the Atlantic slave trade for plantation and domestic labor from 1619 to 1865.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As landowners sought to maximize profits through slave labor and fertility from the soil, they created a system that degraded both enslaved people and the Southern landscape.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Upon the establishment of slave labor on plantations, forests were cleared, swamps were drained, and fragile ecosystems were destroyed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These practices left eroded hillsides, rivers clogged with sterile soil, and lead to the extinction of native species.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Like the people they enslaved for labor, plantation owners viewed the land as disposable, relocating to more fertile prospects once the nutrients had been leeched from the soil and forests had been cut down.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] However, as much as slavery reshaped the Southern landscape, the environment shaped American slavery.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to Silkenat, the enslaved people who worked the land gained extensive knowledge of the surrounding environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] At night, enslaved people would secretly utilize the woods to trap food, visit relatives at neighbouring plantations, and use their knowledge of the environment to escape to freedom.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] While some escaped north, others established communities deep in alligator-infested swamps where plantation owners would not venture.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] African Americans drew upon their environmental knowledge to liberate themselves, later leading to the civil war.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In the Civil War (1861–1865) more powerful long-range rifles and artillery caused high casualty rates of wounding and death.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Union forces had much better medical and hospital facilities, while the supply system failed so often in the Confederacy that for months at a time soldiers marched and fought barefoot, with little medicine available to their overworked doctors.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Union systematically devastated the railway system in the South and ruined many cotton plantations.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Combat operations killed thousands of horses and mules used to pull supplies, artillery and munitions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The South was overwhelmingly rural, with a priority on growing and exporting cotton to textile factories.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Most of the food was imported from the North.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Union blockade shut down most of the cotton exports and nearly all of its food imports.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Union cut off many of its internal rail and river travel routes.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The main Southern meat supply was pork, but the output was sharply reduced by disease and shortages of feed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Hunger and bad nutrition weakened the Confederacy and led to desertions as Confederate soldiers realized their families were at risk of starvation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The war was largely fought in hot, wet regions hosting numerous pandemic diseases.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As a result, sickness rates were high on both sides.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] For both armies disease caused about twice as many deaths as did combat.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The main causes of fatality were diarrhea and dysentery, followed by typhoid fever, pneumonia, malaria and smallpox.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Malaria was widespread across the South.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Union army suffered over 1 million cases of malaria, resulting in about 10,000 deaths.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] It accounted for about 1 in 6 of the 6.5 million episodes of illnesses .
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] More Southerners had immunity but they had many cases and far worse medical treatment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Quinine was the only effective remedy—Union doctors had plenty but the blockade cut off supplies to the South.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Ticks, lice and fleas caused much illness in both armies especially Typhus and Relapsing fever.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Of the 3 million horses and mules in military service during the war, about half died.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The main causes were battle injuries, overwork, diseases like glanders and lack of proper food and care.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In the South the Union army shot horses it did not need to keep them out of Confederate hands.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The population of the Great Plains states, including Minnesota, Dakota, Nebraska, and Kansas, grew from 1.0 million in 1870 to 2.4 million in 1880.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The number of farms in the region tripled, increasing from 99,000 in 1870 to 302,000 in 1880.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The improved acreage (land under cultivation) quintupled, rising from 5.0 million acres to 24.6 million acres during the same period. the new settlers mostly purchased land on generous terms from transcontinental railroads that were given land grants by Washington.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As settlers expanded into the Great Plains in the 19th century, they displaced Native American populations to transform the landscape for European settlement and resource extraction.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As a part of strategized displacement, the U.S.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Army was deployed for the mass slaughter of bison herds, animals essential to Indigenous ways of life in the plains.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Army official, Lieutenant Colonel Dodge, told soldiers, “Kill every buffalo you can!
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] LaPier explains, Native Americans, such as the Lakota Sioux and the Comanche, had hunted bison for centuries, each with their own deep individual connection to the animal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The bison provided them with meat for food, hides for shelter and clothing, and bones for tools, an essential part of Indigenous ways of life on the plains.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Indigenous people hunted in sustainable ways, not affecting the population.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Eradication of the bison caused starvation and stripped Indigenous people of land, nationhood, and culture.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] This new vulnerability allowed settlers to force surviving Native Nations onto reservations.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Close to the turn of the century, there were between 30 and 60 million bison in the Great Plains.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In addition to the subjugation and killing of Native Americans, this drop in population also effected the ecology of the plains.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Bison were a keystone species and without them the entire ecosystem changed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Dead bison meant the end of grazing, wallowing and migrating practices that made the land accommodating of other species.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The insects that had lived in bison dung were the food for birds, turtles, and bats.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Bison would create impressions in the dirt where they rolled, which would later fill with rain, providing homes for tadpoles and frogs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] When the bison no longer exist, these species disappear.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to scholar Danielle Taschereau Mamers, the near extinction of the bison marked not just an ecological catastrophe, but a deliberate campaign of cultural and economic warfare against Indigenous peoples of the Great Plains.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In 1870 to 1920, the center of industrialization expanded from New England and the Mid-Atlantic regions into the Midwest to Chicago and St Louis.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Melosi this became the industrial base of the world's leading industrial power.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Environmental degradation, ignored at first, became an increasing concern regarding sewage, garbage, drinking water, and clean air and adequate medical care..
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Pollution was caused by primarily by coal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] It was the primary energy source to power factories and heat offices and apartments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Its use led to a sharp increase in carbon emissions and air pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The concentration of industries such as steel improved efficiency but increased resource waste and pollution of air and water as urban rivers became dumping grounds for industrial waste.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Residential overcrowding into tenements led to poor sanitation and more sickness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Energy history is the record over four centuries of the transitions from wood and water power, to coal, to oil and natural gas, and most recently renewable energy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Robert Suits, Nathan Matteson, and Elisabeth Moyer, "Energy Transitions in U.S.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Wood was the main fuel for heating, cooking, and basic industry due to abundant forests up and down the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Water wheels in local streams powered early mills in New England and small-scale manufacturing, becoming critical during the early phases of industrialization, 1810s-1840s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] By the late-1800s, wood ("biomass" in the graphs) began to decline as the nation's energy demands soared and forests near growing cities were depleted.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] After 1850 the nation's accelerating industrial growth led to a surge in coal use, spurred by railroads, steam engines, and later, electric power generation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] By the late 19th century, coal overtook wood as the dominant energy source.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Coal was powering factories, heating homes and shops, and was essential for railroads and steel mills.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Bituminous coal. or soft coal dominated.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Coal's preeminence continued into the early 20th century, accounting for up to three-quarters of the national energy supply by World War I.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] A serious challenge was the enormous pollution caused by soft coal in the overcrowded cities.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] There was a growing demand for Smoke abatement.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] New technology and new policies enabled oil and natural gas to move from rarity in 1860 to the dominant fuels by 1920.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Factories switched to the internal combustion engine for power.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] States actively supported the oil industry.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] New giant corporations, especially Rockefeller's Standard Oil Company built a vast network of pipelines which moved energy more cheaply than railroads.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Oil and natural gas replaced coal, especially after World War I and into the mid-20th century.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] One result was smoke abatement, as heavy smoke and smog declined sharply after 1945.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The federal government after 1945 promoted nuclear technology, both for military and peaceful civilian purposes, and financed the rapid increase in nuclear power plants in the 1960s-1970s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] But then nuclear power stalled in the face of radiation dangers and successful anti-nuclear campaigns.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] A decisive event was the accidental release of radiation at Three Mile Island in Pennsylvania in 1979.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Nuclear power plants and related facilities in the United States have often been disproportionately proposed and located in or near communities of color and low-income areas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Native American land or reservations is often affected by these developments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] NECONA urged tribes to institute nuclear-free zones on their lands, successfully facilitating the agreement of 75 tribes by 1997.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Before NECONA's advocacy and success, nuclear facilities posed significant health risks to Native communities.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Prairie Island Nuclear Power Plant, built by Westinghouse for the utility Northern States Power on a sandbar in the middle of the Mississippi River in 1973 and 1974, was located beside the homes, businesses, and childcare center of the Mdewakanton Dakota Prairie Island homeland.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] While the plant produced an estimated 15 percent of Minnesota's power, none benefitted the Mdewakanton Dakota people.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In turn, it actively harmed the environment and population.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The plant did not inform the Prairie Island residents about several safety breaches such as a 30-minute radioactive leak in 1979 where staff were rushed offsite, but the Dakota people were not informed until they discovered the hazard for themselves on the radio.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, the Minnesota Department of Health found that the plant had exposed Prairie Island residents to six times greater risk of cancer.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These environmental impacts were due to the island's limited space for waste.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In 1986, the waste was put into an on-site nuclear dump in reinforced-steel cans outside the plant.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] By 1988, the plant requested permission from the government to store more fuel in dry cask storage, a method which most believed would significantly increase the risk to the tribe.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In turn, the tribe brought a six year long legal battle in opposition to the request.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Although in 1994 Minnesota legislature allowed dry cask storage three blocks from the tribe's childcare center on an interim basis, it was on the terms that a permanent storage facility would be opened by 2004, or the plant would be shut down.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] It was the first instance where a state legislature required a reactor to shut down if it lacked an approved waste disposal site.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Another feature of nuclear power is the need for uranium mining.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] According to environmental historian Traci Brynne Voyles, the 1941 search for uranium to support the Manhattan Project resulted in the discovery and mining of deposits on and near Navajo (Diné) land.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] This discovery brought in a rush of mining companies, however by 1981 the metal was no longer profitable.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] This uranium boom left over 2,000 now-abandoned uranium mines, mills, and tailings piles in its wake.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These sites, once manned by 3,000 Navajo miners, remain open, poorly covered, or insufficiently marked.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The land around them is contaminated by the dangerous nature of uranium: radioactive tailings piles that leach radon gas into the air and water while scattering radioactive debris throughout the ecosystem.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The radioactive contaminants are joined by other toxic contaminants such as arsenic, vanadium, and manganese.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Renewables were 8.4% of total energy, or 8.3 quads.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Renewable energy accounted for 8.4% of total primary energy production and 21% of total utility-scale electricity generation in the United States in 2022.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Since 2019, wind power has been the largest producer of renewable electricity in the country.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Wind power generated 434 terawatt-hours of electricity in 2022, which accounted for 10% of the nation's electricity and 48% of renewable generation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Hydroelectric power is the second-largest producer of renewable electricity in the country, generating around 6.2% of the nation's electricity in 2022 as well as 29% of renewable generation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The United States is the fourth largest producer of hydroelectricity in the world after China, Canada and Brazil.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Solar power provides a growing share of electricity in the country, with over 111.6 GW of installed capacity generating about 3.4% of the country's total electricity supply in 2022, up from 2.8% the previous year.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] President Barack Obama (2009–2017) introduced the goal of using renewable energy to forestall the threat of global warming.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 invested heavily in clean energy and energy efficiency.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] His Clean Power Plan set the first-ever limits on carbon pollution from power plants.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These efforts aimed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, increase renewable energy generation, and foster a cleaner energy sector.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Presidency of Joseph Biden continued and enlarged on Obama's energy initiatives.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In the two Trump administrations, especially Second presidency of Donald Trump that policy was reversed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Denouncing wind and solar as "A Blight On Our Country," Trump rolled back support and subsidies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Instead he prioritized what he calls "reliable, dispatchable" energy sources, especially oil and gas.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] While renewable energy is praised for providing a solution to climate change, the methods of creating infrastructure for such technologies also pose environmental threats.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Minerals such as cobalt, lithium, manganese, and nickel are essential for lithium-ion batteries, which are used in renewable energies like wind and solar to store energy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Mining of these critical minerals present occupational and environmental threats.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] For miners and those who live near mines, cobalt inhalation can cause respiratory toxicity such as hard metal lung disease.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Systemic cobalt toxicity can cause cardiomyopathy, thyroid dysfunction, neurologic dysfunction, and aseptic lymphocyte-dominated vasculitis-associated lesions.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Manganese has been extensively linked to neurotoxicity, neurologic and psychiatric manifestations such as Parkinsonism, motor deficits, cognitive impairment, and psychosis through both occupational and environmental exposure.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The known genotoxin and carcinogen, nickel, is inhaled, ingested, and absorbed through skin.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Lithium exposure is known to be nephrotoxic, thyrotoxic, and causes birth defects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] As mining of these minerals expands, high levels of lifetime cancer risks have been found in samples from environments surrounding mines, with an increased risk for children compared to adults.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Risks for those who live near mines largely comes from contamination of soil, water, plants, and animals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These contaminations have been found to pose a significant risk to environmental and human health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These broader risks disproportionally burden communities already facing structural marginalization, particularly Indigenous nations whose lands, water, and cultural sites are often the locations of mining endeavors.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] In the case of the Hualapai tribe in Arizona, drilling of exploration holes in the 2024 search for lithium coincided with declining sacred spring water levels.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Members of the Hualapai claim mining lithium and other minerals on or near native land brings the construction of roads, ports, and other infrastructure that brings pollution, loss of biodiversity, destruction of cultural sites, and increased violence against Indigenous women.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Hualapai share the same concerns as tribes in Nevada whose sacred land, Thacker Pass, is mined for its large lithium deposit.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Since Thacker pass’ initial approval in 2021, both Indigenous and non-Indigenous people local to the area have forewarned about the environmental impacts.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The company behind the mining project, Lithium Americas, plan to pump 1.7 million gallons of water from the aquifer each year, which ranchers claim will make their land unhospitable by draining the local aquifer.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Lithium Americas also plan to turn 6,000 acres of Thacker Pass into an industrial zone, destroying Native cultural sites.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The industrial zone would consist of 1,000 acres for the pit, 1,000 acres for a tailings facility of hazardous material, and finally backfill, roads, worker facilities, septic systems, fencing, and an onsite sulfuric acid plant.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] These processes all increase concerns for air pollution and metal contamination of groundwater for those who live nearby.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Both the Hualapai land and Thacker Pass are examples of groups and lands in the United States put at risk by the accelerated shift towards renewable resources and need for critical minerals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Among the first pieces of legislation passed following independence was the Land Ordinance of 1785, which provided for the surveying and sale of lands in the area created by state cessions of western land to the national government.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Later, the Northwest Ordinance provided for the political organization of the Northwest Territories (now the states of Michigan, Wisconsin, Ohio, Illinois, and Indiana.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] To encourage settlement of western lands, Congress passed the first of several Homestead Acts in 1862, granting parcels in 40-acre (160,000 m2) increments to homesteaders who would maintain a living on the land for five years, and then they would own it.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Congress also made huge land grants to various railroads working to complete a transcontinental rail system.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The railroad grants included mineral and timber-rich lands so that the railroads could get financing to build.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Again, the plan was that the railroads would sell off the land to get money, and the new transportation network would not use taxpayer money.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] It turned out that much western land was not suited for homesteading because of mountainous terrain, poor soils, lack of available water, and other problems.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] By the early 20th century, the federal government held significant portions of most western states that had simply not been claimed for any use.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Conservationists prevailed upon President Theodore Roosevelt to set aside lands for forest conservation and for special scientific or natural history interest.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] Much land still remained unclaimed even after such reserves had been initially set up.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The US Department of the Interior held millions of acres in the western states, with Arizona and New Mexico joining the union by 1913.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] US President Herbert Hoover proposed to deed the surface rights to the unappropriated lands to the states in 1932, but the states complained that the lands had been overgrazed and would also impose a burden during the cash-strapped state budgets.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p01] The Bureau of Land Management was created to manage much of that land.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Michael Kraft examines the rise and evolution of conservation and environmental politics and policies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] "Conservation" originated in the late 19th century as a movement built around the conservation of natural resources and an attempt to stave off air, water, and land pollution.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] By the 1970s environmentalism evolved into a much more sophisticated control regime, one that employed the Environmental Protection Agency to slow environmental degradation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In the 1960s and 1970s the conservation movement morphed into modern environmentalism.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The seminal moment that ignited the transition occurred in 1962 with the publication of Rachel Carson's groundbreaking book, *Silent Spring*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Carson's urgent message warned about the perils of harmful chemical pollutants, notably substances like DDT with immediate benefits but long-term detrimental impacts, resonated with an educated audience deeply concerned about quality-of-life issues.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The environmental awakening spurred by Carson's work was further fueled by events like the 1969 televised oil spill off the California coast.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It prompted many to join mainstream environmental organizations led by visionaries such as David Brower of the Sierra Club.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The momentum was bolstered by the inaugural Earth Day in 1970.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] President Richard Nixon took proactive steps through executive actions and collaboration with Congress to enact pivotal legislation establishing regulatory frameworks that curbed air and water pollution and mitigated adverse effects of corporate greed and rampant consumerism.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The emergence of a more radical activism came in the late 1970s and early 1980s, exemplified by chemical disaster at Love Canal in 1977, and a battle in 1982 against a PCB toxic waste dump in a Black community in North Carolina.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The result was confrontational grassroots environmentalism that marked the genesis of the "environmental justice" movement.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It focused on issues of toxic substances and addressing concerns of "environmental racism." The term “environmental racism” refers to the way in which people of color are often not valued the same as their White counterparts, and how these standings effect the environment around these communities.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It describes how state and corporate policies, practices, and initiatives may target communities of color, putting the burden of environmental degradation on their land.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Therefore, “environmental racism” is institutional policies and practices that affect the health outcomes and living conditions of people and communities differently and unequally due to their race and color.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The collective efforts during this period laid a foundation for ongoing environmental advocacy and policy development aimed at safeguarding our planet for future generations.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The term "conservation" was coined by American forester Gifford Pinchot in 1907.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He told his close friend President Theodore Roosevelt who used it for a national Conference of Governors in 1908 gained national attention regarding priorities for conservation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The American movement received its inspiration from 19th century Romantic writings that exalted the inherent value of nature, quite apart from human usage.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Author Henry David Thoreau (1817–1862) made key philosophical contributions that exalted nature.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Thoreau was interested in peoples' relationship with nature and studied this by living close to nature in a simple life.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He published his experiences in the book *Walden,* which argued that people should become intimately close with nature.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] British and German standards were also influential in designing American policies and training.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Bernhard Fernow (1851–1923) emigrated from Germany in 1876 and became was the third chief of the Department of Agriculture's Division of Forestry, 1886 to 1898.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He helped design what in 1905 became the Forest Service.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Schenck (1868–1955), another German expert, migrated to the United States in 1895 and helped shape the education of foresters.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Hays and Clayton Koppes, the conservation movement was launched into the national political arena in 1908 by President Theodore Roosevelt and his top advisor Gifford Pinchot.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It represented the essence of the Progressive Era and therefore was driven by the primary values of efficiency, equity, and esthetics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Efficiency was to be achieved by full-time experts in the federal bureaucracy (headed by Pinchot) who would use the latest scientific results to manage the public domain to eliminate waste.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] These disinterested experts would prevent the corruption sought by selfish business interests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Equity meant that natural resources were the province of all the people and should not be plundered by special interests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Instead, resources should be apportioned broadly and equitably.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] However "all the people" in practice meant white farm owners and ranchers who obtained a free water supply or access to free grazing land.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The esthetic theme was an appeal to and upscale white tourists who wanted a taste of wilderness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Wild and scenic lands should be set aside in national parks, not for their intrinsic value, but to provide free recreation, refresh the spirit weakened by urbanization, and even upgrade "sissies" into virile outdoorsmen.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In the Great Depression of the 1930s the New Deal of President Franklin D.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt expanded the E-E-E tradition to include poor whites, with his key advisors being Harry Hopkins and Harold L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The main programs reached two million poor unemployed young men through the Civilian Conservation Corps, while the Tennessee Valley Authority to modernize millions of traditional people trapped in an impoverished, isolated region.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Both conservationists and preservationists spoke out in political debates during the Progressive Era (the 1890s–early 1920s), with an opposition emerging in the 1920s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The debate between conservation and preservation reached its peak in the public debates over the construction of California's Hetch Hetchy dam in Yosemite National Park which supplies the water supply of San Francisco.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] President Roosevelt put conservationist issues high on the national agenda.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He worked with all the major figures of the movement, especially his chief advisor on the matter, Gifford Pinchot and was deeply committed to efficiency in conserving natural resources.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He encouraged the Newlands Reclamation Act of 1902 to promote federal construction of dams to irrigate small farms and placed 230 million acres (360,000 mi2 or 930,000 km2) under federal protection.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt set aside more federal land for national parks and nature preserves than all of his predecessors combined.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt established the United States Forest Service, signed into law the creation of five national parks, and signed the 1906 Antiquities Act, under which he proclaimed 18 new national monuments.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He also established the first 51 bird reserves, four game preserves, and 150 national forests, including Shoshone National Forest, the nation's first.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The area of the United States that he placed under public protection totals approximately 230,000,000 acres (930,000 km2).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Gifford Pinchot had been appointed by McKinley as chief of Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1905, his department gained control of the national forest reserves.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Pinchot promoted private use (for a fee) under federal supervision.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1907, Roosevelt designated 16 million acres (65,000 km2) of new national forests just minutes before a deadline.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In May 1908, Roosevelt sponsored the Conference of Governors held in the White House, with a focus on natural resources and their most efficient use.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt delivered the opening address: "Conservation as a National Duty".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1903, Roosevelt toured the Yosemite Valley with John Muir, who had a very different view of conservation, and tried to minimize commercial use of water resources and forests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Working through the Sierra Club he founded, Muir succeeded in 1905 in having Congress transfer the Mariposa Grove and Yosemite Valley to the federal government.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Theodore Roosevelt's view on conservationism remained dominant for decades.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] For example, the New Deal under Franklin D.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt authorised the building of many large-scale dams and water projects, as well as the expansion of the National Forest System to buy out sub-marginal farms.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1937, the Pittman–Robertson Federal Aid in Wildlife Restoration Act was signed into law, providing funding for state agencies to carry out their conservation efforts.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] "Environmentalism" emerged on the national agenda in 1970, with Republican Richard Nixon playing a major role, especially with his creation of the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] From 1962 to 1998, the grass roots movement founded 772 national organizations focused primarily on environmental protection or pollution abatement.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, many other organizations adopted such goals in addition to their primary goal, such as the American Lung Association.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Brulle identified over 6,000 national and regional organizations, plus another 20,000 or more at the local and state levels that were working on behalf of a multitude of environmental causes in the year 2000.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] According to historian Tim Lehman, concerns were first raised in the 20th century regarding the long-term adequacy of the nation's agricultural lands.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] At the federal level studies were made and programs were proposed and some launched to preserve farmlands from conversion to other uses.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] An awareness of the need for agricultural conservation followed a history of agricultural abundance, as seen in the rapid settlement of western lands in the 1850s to 1880s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The new theme emerged in the Progressive conservation movement, in Hugh Hammond Bennett's soil conservation crusade, and the land utilization movement of the 1920s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The New Deal made a major national program of land use planning.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] A land acquisition program, soil conservation districts, and county land use planning agreement all contained elements of federal agricultural land use planning, but none of these policies were entirely successful.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Scarcity issues faded during the 1950s and 1960s as agricultural productivity soared.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The publication of Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* in 1962 energized the environmental movement and brought a new awareness in how industrialized agriculture misused the available land with dangerous chemicals.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Decades of suburbanization, rapid national and global population growth, renewed worries about soil erosion, fears of oil and water shortages, and the sudden increase in farm exports beginning in 1972 all were worrisome threats to the long-term supply of good farmland.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Carter administration in the late 1970s supported initiatives like the National Agricultural Lands Survey and liberals in Congress introduced legislation to control suburban sprawl.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] However the Reagan administration and the Department of Agriculture were opposed to new regulations, and no major program was enacted.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The success of Reagan in 1980 was facilitated by the rise of popular opposition to public lands reform and a return to laissez-faire ideology.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] For example, out west in the 1970s the Sagebrush Rebellion arose, demanding less environmental regulation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Conservatives drew on new organizational networks of think tanks such as The Heritage Foundation, as well as well-funded industry groups, the Republican Party state organizations, and new right-wing citizen-oriented grass-roots organizations.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] They deployed the traditional strategy based on the rights of owners to control their property; on the protection of mineral extraction rights; and on the right to hunt and recreate and to pursue happiness unencumbered by the federal government at the expense of resource conservation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Reagan's top appointments in the environment field were James G.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Watt as Secretary of the Interior and Anne Gorsuch as head of the EPA.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] They tried to help the Reagan agenda by slashing spending and lowering morale.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Both proved incompetent at the jobs; they picked fights with friends and foes and soon made fools of themselves.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Environmentalists seized on their opportunity and made Watt and Gorsuch the centerpiece of their campaigns of ridicule.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Reagan realized his mistake and fired the two.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He appointed a close friend and troubleshooter, William Clark at Interior.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Clark successfully turned off the spotlight and kept the peace.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] At EPA, Reagan appointed William Ruckelshaus, the EPA's first director and a committed environmentalist.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] William Cronon has criticized advocates for assuming that "wilderness" and "nature" have a reality beyond their creation in the human imagination.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Most of the agencies dealing with conservation (before 1970) and environmentalism (since 1970) are based in the Interior Department, formed in 1849.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The National Park Service was created in 1916.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It included Yellowstone National Park, which in 1872 became the world's first national park.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1956, the Fish and Wildlife Service became the manager of lands reserved for wildlife.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Grazing Service and the United States General Land Office were combined to create the Bureau of Land Management in 1946.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1976 the Federal Land Policy and Management Act became the national policy for retaining public land for federal ownership.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It is responsible for the management and conservation of most federal lands and natural resources.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It also administers programs relating to Native Americans, Alaska Natives, Native Hawaiians, territorial affairs, and insular areas of the United States, as well as programs related to historic preservation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] As of mid-2004, the department managed 507 million acres (2,050,000 km2) of surface land, or about one-fifth of the land in the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It manages 476 dams and 348 reservoirs through the Bureau of Reclamation, 433 national parks, monuments, historical sites, etc. through the National Park Service, and 544 national wildlife refuges through the Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] From the early 1900s to the present, there has been a fierce rivalry over control of forests between the Department of Agriculture and the Department of the Interior.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] From 1905 to the present the main forestry unit has been in the Department of Agriculture.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The concept of national forests was born from Theodore Roosevelt's conservation group, Boone and Crockett Club, due to concerns regarding poaching Yellowstone National Park beginning as early as 1875.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1876, Congress formed the office of Special Agent in the Department of Agriculture to assess the quality and conditions of forests in the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Hough was appointed the head of the office.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1881, the office was expanded into the newly formed **Division of Forestry**.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Forest Reserve Act of 1891 authorized withdrawing land from the public domain as forest reserves managed by the Department of the Interior.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] However, the Transfer Act of 1905 transferred the management of forest reserves from the United States General Land Office of the Interior Department to the Bureau of Forestry in the Agriculture department under the new name **United States Forest Service**.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Gifford Pinchot was the first United States Chief Forester in the Presidency of Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Significant federal legislation affecting the Forest Service includes the Weeks Act of 1911, the Taylor Grazing Act of 1934, P.L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] 73-482; the Multiple Use – Sustained Yield Act of 1960, P.L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] 88-577; the National Forest Management Act, P.L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] 94-588; the National Environmental Policy Act, P.L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] 91–190; the Cooperative Forestry Assistance Act, P.L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] 95-313; and the Forest and Rangelands Renewable Resources Planning Act, P.L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Army Corps of Engineers is in charge of navigable waterways, and has built many of the major dams.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The **Tennessee Valley Authority** (**TVA**) is a federally owned electric utility coverings all of Tennessee and portions of nearby states.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The TVA was created in 1933 as part of a New Deal agency to build dams on the Tennessee River to provide flood control, electricity generation, fertilizer manufacturing, regional planning, economic development to the Tennessee Valley.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The region was a very poor part of Appalachia and out of contact with the modern industrial and agricultural economy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Unlike private utility companies TVA was envisioned as regional economic development agency that would work to help modernize the region's economy and society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Its chairman Arthur Morgan was a visionary, who wanted a model for modernizing traditional society.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Some New Dealers hoped it would be a model for other regions, but others strongly disagreed and the president was undecided.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Any hope for opening "Seven Little TVAs" across the country died when conservatives regained control of Congress in 1938 and ended liberal experimentation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Environmental Protection Agency** (**EPA**) is an independent federal agency created by an executive order of President President Nixon in 1970 and is part of the executive branch of the government.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It reports to the president and was not created by act of Congress.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The primary mission of the EPA is to protect human health and safeguard the natural environment (air, water and land) of the nation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The EPA was established to combine into a single agency many of the existing federal government activities of research and development, monitoring, setting of standards, compliance and enforcement related to protection of the environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Its most important role is to evaluate every Environmental impact statement that is required whenever a federal role is involved.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Thereby EPA has the power to demand changes from most federal agencies to protect the environment according to EPA's standards.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In addition, the Environmental impact statement allows a public role—private citizen watchdogs can and often do sue to tie up proposed non-government projects for years.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 2000 to 2010 the budget held fairly steady at $7.6 to $8.4 billion (with no adjustment for inflation).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In terms of objectives, 13% is budgeted for clean air and global climate change, 36% for clean and safe water, 24% for land preservation and restoration, 17% for healthy communities and ecosystems, and 11% for compliance and environmental stewardship.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 2008 it had a staff of about 18,000 people in headquarters and departmental or divisional offices, 10 regional offices, and over 25 laboratories located across the nation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] More than half of the staff are engineers, scientists and environmental protection specialists.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The others include legal counsel, financial, public affairs and computer specialists.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] President Nixon, on July 9, 1970, told Congress of his plan to create the EPA by combining parts of three federal departments, three bureaus, three administrations and many other offices into the new single, independent agency to be known as the *Environmental Protection Agency*.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Congress had 60 days to reject the proposal, but opinion was favorable and the reorganization took place without legislation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] On December 2, 1970, the EPA was officially established and began operation under director William Ruckelshaus.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The EPA began by consolidating 6550 employees from different agencies in several cabinet-level departments into a new agency with a $1.4 billion budget.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Kraft notes that despite its limited charter from 1970, over time EPA has expanded its regulatory function and jousted with the forces of business and economic development.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Kraft considers the next major transition in environmental policy to be the process of insuring the "sustainability" of resources through a coalition of interests ranging from policymakers to business leaders, scholars, and individual citizens.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] At the turn of the 21st century, these often competing groups were wrestling with disparate environmental, economic, and social values.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Russell shows that from 1970 to 1993, the EPA devoted more of its resources to human health issues, notably cancer prevention, than to the protection of nonhuman species.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The limited scope of environmental protection was due to a variety of reasons.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] An institutional culture favored human health issues because most employees were trained in this area.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The emphasis on cancer came from the legal division's discovery that judges were more persuaded by arguments about the carcinogenicity of chemicals than by threats to nonhumans.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The views of the agency leaders, who followed politically realistic courses, also played an important part in shaping the EPA's direction.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Those supporting ecological issues acquired a new tool in the 1980s with the development of risk assessments so that advocates of ecological protection could use language framed by advocates of human health to protect the environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Complaints about federal management of public lands constantly roil relations between public lands users (ranchers, miners, researchers, off-road vehicle enthusiasts, hikers, campers and conservation advocates) and the agencies and environmental regulation on the other.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Ranchers complain that grazing fees are too high and that grazing regulations are too onerous despite environmentalist complaints that the opposite is true and that promised improvements to grazing on federal lands do not occur.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Miners complain of restricted access to claims, or to lands to prospect.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Researchers complain of the difficulty of getting research permits, only to encounter other obstacles in research, including uncooperative permit-holders and, especially in archaeology, vandalized sites with key information destroyed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Off-road vehicle users want free access, but hikers and campers and conservationists complain grazing is not regulated enough and that some mineral lease holders abuse other lands or that off-road vehicle destroy the resource.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Conservation was a minor issue for most presidents.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Theodore Roosevelt carved a leadership role that several successors followed.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt was a prominent conservationist, putting the issue high on his national agenda.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He changed the land by creating 50 wildlife refuges, 18 national monuments, and five national parks, and above all by publicizing conservation issues.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt's conservation efforts were aimed not just at environment protection, but also at ensuring that society as a whole, rather than just select individuals or companies, benefited from the country's natural resources.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] His key adviser on conservation matters was Gifford Pinchot, the head of the Bureau of Forestry.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt increased Pinchot's power over environmental issues by transferring control over national forests from the Department of the Interior to the Bureau of Forestry, which was part of the Agriculture Department.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Pinchot's agency was renamed to the United States Forest Service, and Pinchot presided over the implementation of assertive conservationist policies in national forests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Under William Howard Taft, Pinchot had a heavily publicized dispute over environmental policy with Secretary of the Interior Richard A.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Ballinger that led to Pinchot's dismissal and to Roosvelt's break with Taft in 1912.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt relied on the Newlands Reclamation Act of 1902, which promoted federal construction of dams to irrigate small farms and placed 230 million acres (360,000 mi2 or 930,000 km2) under federal protection.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1906, Congress passed the Antiquities Act, granting the president the power to create national monuments in federal lands.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt set aside more federal land, national parks, and nature preserves than all of his predecessors combined.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt established the Inland Waterways Commission to coordinate construction of water projects for both conservation and transportation purposes, and in 1908 he hosted the Conference of Governors.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] This was the first time governors had ever met together and the goal was to boost and coordinate support for conservation.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt then established the National Conservation Commission to take an inventory of the nation's natural resources.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] To reach a broad national audience of state leaders, and obtain heavy media coverage, President Roosevelt sponsored the first ever Conference of Governors.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It was held in the White House May 13–15, 1908.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Pinchot, at that time Chief Forester of the U.S., was the primary mover of the conference, and a progressive conservationist, who strongly believed in the scientific and efficient management of natural resources on the federal level.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He was also a prime mover of the previous Inland Waterways Commission, which recommended such a meeting the previous October.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The focus of the conference was on natural resources and their proper use.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt delivered the opening address: "Conservation as a National Duty." Among those speaking were leading industrialists, such as James J.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Hill, politicians, and resource experts.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Andrew Carnegie, a leading philanthropist was in attendance.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The speeches emphasized both the nation's need to exploit renewable resources and the differing situations of the various states, requiring different plans.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] This Conference was a seminal event in the history of conservationism; it brought the issue to public attention in a highly visible way.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The next year saw two outgrowths of the Conference: the National Conservation Commission, which Roosevelt and Pinchot set up with representatives from the states and Federal agencies, and the First National Conservation Commission, which Pinchot led as an assembly of private conservation interests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt's policies faced opposition from both liberal environmental activists like John Muir and conservative proponents of laissez-faire like Senator Henry M.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The backlash to Roosevelt's ambitious policies prevented further conservation efforts in the final years of Roosevelt's presidency and would later contribute to the Pinchot–Ballinger controversy during the Taft administration.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt had a lifelong interest in the environment and conservation starting with his youthful interest in forestry on his family estate.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Although he was never an outdoorsman or sportsman on the scale of his distant cousin Theodore Roosevelt, their presidential roles in conservation were comparable.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The governor worked closely with Harry Hopkins and in 1933 brought Hopkins to Washington to use the New York experience to shape the national programs of work relief.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal was active in expanding, funding, and promoting the National Park and National Forest systems.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Their popularity soared, from three million visitors a year at the start of the decade to 15.5 million in 1939.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Every state had its own state parks, and Roosevelt made sure that WPA and CCC projects were set up to upgrade them as well as the national systems.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] From 1933 to 1942, the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) enrolled 3.4 million young men for six months service.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It built 13,000 miles (21,000 kilometres) of trails, planted two billion trees, and upgraded 125,000 miles (201,000 kilometres) of dirt roads.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] CCC made permanent "improvements" on 118 million acres (triple the size of Connecticut).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, the parents received $25 a month while their sones were away.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Cammere, the energetic head of the National Park system, realized that helping solve the unemployment crisis was Roosevelt's main goal.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The conservation projects of the Park and Forest services were dramatically expanded.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] According to Richard Lowitt, the New Deal Interior Department led by Secretary Harold L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Ickes, emphasized economic benefits from hydroelectric power.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The department sought to build "the foundations for a more stable economy in the West that would expand enormously and bring in its wake a rising standard of living, increased population, and a greater measure of equality with other sections of the country".
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The New Deal ignored the fears of the upper-class purists who realized their single goal of preserving wilderness instead of "improving" it was being undermined.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] When unemployment practically ended in 1942, many of the New Deal agencies closed down permanently, including the WPA and CCC.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] New conservation programs were put on hold unless they contributed to the war effort.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Army Corps of Engineers turned to military construction and took charge of building the atomic bomb.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The TVA played a major role in producing the uranium and plutonium used in the bombs dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Vice President took over when Roosevelt died in April 1945.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Truman never enjoyed his youth on the farm and had no interest in the outdoors, nor did his Interior Secretary Oscar L.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] However both Truman and Chapman were keenly aware of the patronage advantages to the Democratic Party in large dam projects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] They sponsored a major expansion with no concern for negative environmental impact.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] After the war ended the Corps of Engineers built 400 dams and 3400 flood control projects, while TVA added 4 dams, and the Bureau of Reclamation added 41.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Water projects continued at a fast pace, with 11,000 new dams in the 1950s and 19,000 in the 1960s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The "Big Dam Era" was made possible by very expensive combinations of high dams, powerful turbines, and high-tension long-distance transmission lines whereby electrical utilities brought power to customers hundreds of miles away.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The era began in the 1930s and was practically over by 1970.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Meanwhile, the environmental movement was starting to form.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Aldo Leopold published a highly influential book in 1949, *A Sand County Almanac*, which helped define environmental ethics.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It eventually sold more than two million copies.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In terms of ideology, liberals (and the Democratic Party) wanted national control of natural resources—the level at which organized ideological pressures were effective.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Conservatives (and the Republican Party) wanted state or local control, whereby the financial benefit to local businesses and jobs could be decisive.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In a debate going back to the early 20th century, preservationists wanted to protect the inherent natural beauty of the national parks, whereas economic maximizers wanted to build dams and divert water flows.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He was a businessman with little interest in the environment who allegedly promoted "giveaways" to mining companies regardless of environmental damage.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Eisenhower's personal activity on environmental issues came in foreign policy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He supported the UN convention of 1958 that provided a strong foundation for international accords governing the use of the world's high seas, especially regarding fishing interests.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Eisenhower also promoted the peaceful use of atomic energy for the production of electricity, with strong controls against diversion into nuclear weapons.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] However, there was little attention to nuclear waste.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Kennedy was a city boy like his constituents.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He did not hunt or fish, hike or explore, nor seek out the wilderness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He did greatly enjoy the ocean and the seashore but otherwise the environment and environmentalism bored him.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The 1962 publication of *Silent Spring* by Rachel Carson brought new attention to environmentalism and the danger that pollution and pesticide poisoning (i.e., DDT) posed to public health.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Johnson succeeded the assassinated president in November 1963, he retained Kennedy's staunchly pro-environment Secretary of the Interior, Stewart Udall.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Johnson helped pass a series a series of bills designed to protect the environment.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He signed into law the Clean Air Act of 1963, which had been proposed by Kennedy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Clean Air Act set emission standards for stationary emitters of air pollutants and directed federal funding to air quality research.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1965, the act was amended by the Motor Vehicle Air Pollution Control Act, which directed the federal government to establish and enforce national standards for controlling the emission of pollutants from new motor vehicles and engines.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1967, Johnson and Senator Edmund Muskie led passage of the Air Quality Act of 1967, which increased federal subsidies for state and local pollution control programs.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] During his time as president, Johnson signed over 300 conservation measures into law, forming the legal basis of the modern environmental movement.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In September 1964, he signed a law establishing the Land and Water Conservation Fund, which aids the purchase of land used for federal and state parks.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] That same month, Johnson signed the Wilderness Act, which established the National Wilderness Preservation System; saving 9.1 million acres of forestland from industrial development.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1965, Muskie led passage of the Water Quality Act of 1965, though conservatives stripped a provision of the act that would have given the federal government the authority to set clean water standards.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The Wild and Scenic Rivers Act of 1968 established the National Wild and Scenic Rivers System.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The system includes more than 220 rivers, and covers more than 13,400 miles of rivers and streams.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The National Trails System Act of 1968 created a nationwide system of scenic and recreational trails.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] As First Lady and trusted presidential confidant, Lady Bird Johnson helped establish the public environmental movement in the 1960s.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] She worked to beautify Washington, D.C. by planting thousands of flowers, set up the White House Natural Beauty Conference, and lobbied Congress for the president's full range of environmental initiatives.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1965, she took the lead in calling for passage of the Highway Beautification Act.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The act called for control of outdoor advertising, including removal of certain types of signs, along the nation's growing Interstate Highway System and the existing federal-aid primary highway system.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] It also required certain junkyards along Interstate or primary highways to be removed or screened and encouraged scenic enhancement and roadside development.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Nixon came late to the conservation movement.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Environmental policy had not been a significant issue in the 1968 election, and the media rarely asked about the subject.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] The president then introduced 36 environmental initiatives and pushed most of them through.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] He strongly supported advisors who deeply believed in environmentalism, especially Russell E.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Train, John Ehrlichman, William Ruckelshaus, and John C.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In June 1970, Nixon announced the formation of the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), using an Executive order that did not require Congressional approval.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Other breakthrough initiatives supported by Nixon included the Clean Air Act of 1970, and the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] His National Environmental Policy Act required environmental impact statements for many Federal projects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, he put protection of the global environment on the international diplomatic agenda for the first time in world history.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Then Nixon reversed himself and in 1972 he vetoed the Clean Water Act —objecting not to the policy goals of the legislation but to the amount of money to be spent on them, which he deemed excessive.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] After Congress overrode his veto, Nixon impounded the funds he deemed unjustifiable.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Political scientists Byron Daines and Glenn Sussman identify six major achievements for which they give credit to Nixon.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] Historians pose a strange paradox regarding Nixon.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] In 1970-1971 he unexpectedly emerged as a great environmentalist who deserves credit for several of the most important environmental laws in American history.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] By 1972, however, he suddenly moved far to the right, despising environmentalists as left-wing fanatics who would bankrupt the economy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p02] For subsequent presidents see Environmental policy of the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] There are a multitude of environmental organizations—over 160 are covered at the List of environmental and conservation organizations in the United States.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] A critical transition took place after World War II that turned these groups into activist organizations working to save the Wilderness.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] The clientele for the clubs had been an upper-class conservative Republican audience with close ties to big business.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] They enjoyed expensive and exotic vacations at uncrowded wilderness sites.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] The older leaders retired and were replaced by men with a mission, especially Howard Zahniser at the Wilderness Society in 1945 and David Brower at the Sierra Club in 1952.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] They were dismayed at the aggressive plans put forward by the "Iron Triangle" that controlled conservation policy.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] The Iron Triangle was the informal backstage coalition of key members of Congress, plus leaders of the major federal agencies, plus local businessmen keen on speeding up economic development by using natural resources.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] After a decade of depression and war, the nation was ready to move ahead.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] The Bureau of Reclamation took the lead with an elaborate plan to develop dams on the Colorado River for the benefit of the economies of Arizona, California, Colorado, Nevada, New Mexico, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] The centerpiece would be a huge new Echo Park Dam inside Dinosaur National Monument.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] Zahniser and Brower, working with 30 other groups, launched recruiting drives to bring in middle class members with idealistic goals to fight the destruction of the wilderness at Echo Park.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] They raised money for staff; mobilized local branches; and flooded the market with glossy magazines featuring nature photography by the likes of Ansel Adams; and petitioned local, state and national politicians.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] They convinced Congress to delete Echo Park Dam from the Colorado River Storage Project in 1955, but had to agree on an alternative dam site at Glen Canyon Dam.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] They went on to oppose other grandiose projects.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] To make their goals permanent Zahniser drafted an ambition "Wilderness Act" designed to permanently protect 50 million acres of wilderness with no commercial activities such as mining or hydroelectric power dams.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] In the end he achieved a Wilderness Act in 1964 that protected 9 million acres and set a national standard, while mobilizing grass roots voters and setting a model of activism for other national and local organizations to emulate in challenging the Iron Triangle.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] The Sierra Club is a major environmental organization.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] It was founded in May 1892, by preservationist John Muir (1838–1914).
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] He became the first president, serving for 20 years.
[src:environmental-history-of-the-united-states/environmental-history-of-the-united-states-p03] Instead it provided its upscale clientele with outdoor adventures, such as guided tours, wilderness camping and mountain climbing.
